(120, 108, 42, '<ul>\r\n	<li>Created a new NAT Network and named it&nbsp;NATNetwork2.</li>\r\n	<li>From Virtual Box accessed the Kali Linux machine&#39;s settings and from&nbsp;the &#39;Networks&#39; section configured the network to the new NAT Network (NATNetwork2).</li>\r\n	<li>Repeated the above settings with the installed Ubuntu machine.</li>\r\n	<li>Now started both the machines and opened terminals in them.</li>\r\n	<li>Noted both the machine&#39;s IP Addresses using the command &#39;ifconfig&#39;/&#39;ip addr&#39;.</li>\r\n	<li>Pinged Ubuntu machine from Kali Linux using the command &#39;ping 10.0.2.4&#39;.(Screenshot- 684)</li>\r\n	<li>Pinged Kali Linux from Ubuntu using the command &#39;ping 10.0.2.5&#39;. (Screenshot- 683)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The pings were successful..!! Please find the attached screenshots.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>Low RAM to run both machines parallelly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Update: Updated RAM.</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Creating NAT Network and connecting a group of machines on it.</li>\r\n	<li>Pinging machines from one another.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-07-27', '2021-07-27', 1, '4', 'Y', 0, '2021-07-27 11:29:46', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(121, 109, 42, '<p>Successful Ping to&nbsp;Windows machine using the name from the Ubuntu terminal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Steps:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Note</strong>: Make sure that both the machines&nbsp;are on the same network. Try pinging with Ip Address first.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Note the IP Address of the target Windows machine ((Screenshot- 696)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(1) Open the terminal in the Ubuntu machine and edit the host file.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(2) To open the hosts file, run the command- &#39;sudo nano /etc/hosts&#39;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(3) Now when the file is opened with nano file editor, add the IP Address and a Name of the Target Windows machine in a single line separated by minimum one space. Format- &#39;&lt;IPAddress&gt;&nbsp; &lt;Name&gt;&#39;.&nbsp;(Screenshot- 695)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(4) Save the file and exit the editor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(5) Now run the ping command using the name which was defined&nbsp;in hosts file- &#39;ping sahebkali&#39;&nbsp;(Screenshot- 694)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ping was successful..!! (Screenshot- 694)</p>\r\n', '<p>Not enough machine memory to run both the Virtual machines parallelly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Error while modifying the hosts file.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Adding host to the Linux hosts file</li>\r\n	<li>pinging the remote machine using its name.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-07-22', '2021-08-05', 1, '4', 'Y', 0, '2021-08-05 14:50:14', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(122, 110, 42, '<p>Installed SSH connection between Ubuntu(as a server) and Windows(as a client).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Place both the Machines on the same network (here I placed both the machines on a NAT Network)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Setting up Ubuntu Machine for SSH Connection:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(1) Open the Terminal in Ubuntu Machine for Installing the OpenSSH Server.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(2) Run the command &#39;<big><small>sudo apt-get install openssh-server&#39;</small></big></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Setting up Windows Machine as a Client for SSH connection:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(3) From the&nbsp;window&#39;s browser download and install &#39;PuTTY&#39; software.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(4) Open the PuTTY from the windows machine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(5) Open the Ubuntu machine and note down its IP Address and one user name.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(6) Get back to the Windows machine and Enter the IP Address of the Ubuntu machine in the PuTTY. <em>&nbsp;(Screenshot-697)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(7) Click on the &#39;OPEN&#39; button in the bottom right of the PuTTY window.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(8) A new window will pop up asking to Enter the User name and Password of the Ubuntu user. Enter the credentials and the terminal of the ubuntu machine is accessible with root privileges (assuming the user of ubuntu used to login has root privileges)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em>&nbsp;(Screenshot-698)</em></p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Installing SSH Connection between two machines and accessing one machine from another, present on the same network.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-08-06', '2021-08-07', 1, '4', 'Y', 0, '2021-08-07 05:39:15', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(123, 111, 42, '<p>Successfully accessed the remote Windows machine from Ubuntu. <em>(Screenshot- 700)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Steps:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(1)</strong> Enable RDP in the remote Windows machine. i.e., Open the control panel from the windows machine, and in the &#39;System&#39; section click on the &#39;Allow remote access&#39;. Enable it and save the settings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(2)</strong> Now from the Ubuntu machine open the Remmina application. Mostly Remmina comes preinstalled in Ubuntu OS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(3)</strong> In Remmina click on the &#39;New connection profile&#39; present on the top left corner of the window.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(4)</strong> Enter the IP address of the remote windows machine in the &#39;Server section&#39; and also the user credentials of the remote machine through which you wish to log in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(Screenshot- 701)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(5)</strong> Now click on &#39;Save and Connect&#39; button at the bottom of window.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And the windows machine&#39;s remote access is gained from the present ubuntu machine. <em>(Screenshot- 699, 700)</em></p>\r\n', '<p>Error showing &#39;cannot connect to the RDP Server&#39; while initiating remote access using&nbsp;the Remmina.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Solution: Created another new user on the remote machine and was able to connect.</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Establishing remote access connection of windows machine from&nbsp;the Linux based machine.</li>\r\n	<li>Using Remmina- A tool of Ubuntu used to establish connections such as RDP, SSH, etc.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-08-06', '2021-08-08', 1, '4', 'Y', 0, '2021-08-07 20:24:08', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(124, 112, 42, '<ul>\r\n	<li>Learned the Overview of Group Policies.</li>\r\n	<li>Downloaded and Installed Group policy editor. <em>(Screenshot- 295, 296, 297)</em></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Group Policy is a feature of Windows that facilitates a wide variety of advanced settings that network administrators can use to control the working environment of users and computer accounts in Active Directory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It essentially provides a centralized place for administrators to manage and configure operating systems, applications, and users&rsquo; settings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Group Policies, when used correctly, can enable you to increase the security of user&rsquo;s computers and help defend against both insider threats and external attacks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A Group Policy Object (GPO) is a group of settings that are created using the Microsoft Management Console (MMC) Group Policy Editor.<br />\r\nGPOs can be associated with a single or numerous Active Directory containers, including sites, domains, or organizational units (OUs).<br />\r\nThe MMC allows users to create GPOs that define registry-based policies, security options, software installation, and much more.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Windows straight out-of-the-box isn&rsquo;t exactly secure. There are numerous gaps in security, most of which can be addressed using GPOs.<br />\r\nWithout plugging these gaps, you leave yourself exposed to a plethora of security threats.</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Overview of Group Policies in Windows.</li>\r\n	<li>Group Policy Objects(GPO).</li>\r\n	<li>Installing and Running Group Policy Editor.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-05-02', '2021-05-02', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-05-03 12:16:13', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(125, 113, 42, '<ul>\r\n	<li>Created a New Standard user using Control Panel and Windows settings</li>\r\n	<li>Switched user to newly created user. Using Ctl+Alt+Delete.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>(Screenshot- 298, 299, 300)</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Creating New users in Windwos.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-05-03', '2021-05-03', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-05-03 13:06:00', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(126, 114, 42, '<p>Prevention of&nbsp;a newly created user from logging in using Group&nbsp;policy editor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Steps to do so:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(1) Open the Group policy editor using CMD command- &#39;gpedit.msc&#39;, This opens a new window of Local Group Policy editor <em>(Screenshot- 304)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(2) In the editor access dropdowns- Computer configuration &gt; Windows settings &gt; Security settings&gt; Local policies &gt; User rights assignment.<em>&nbsp;(Screenshot- 301)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(3) Coming to the User rights assignment,&nbsp;Search for the &#39;Deny log on locally&#39;&nbsp;policy on the Right Side of the window.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(4) Open the&nbsp;Deny log on locally policy by double-clicking on the name. From the new window opened click on the &#39;Add user or group&#39; button to add the required user for restricting login.&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 305)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(5) Enter the user name and click on check names and once the user name is loaded, Apply the settings. <em>(Screenshot- 305,303)</em></p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Accessing Group policy editor.</li>\r\n	<li>Restricting a particular user or a group of users from logging into the system.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '2021-05-03', '2021-05-03', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-05-03 19:04:18', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
