(158, 145, 42, '<p>For a long time, Shodan was the only IoT search engine. In the year 2013, a free rival called Censys emerged (unlike Shodan&rsquo;s fees).<br />\r\nCensys is also a search engine for the IoT relying on the same basic principles, but, as its creators say, more precise when it comes to searching for vulnerabilities.<br />\r\nCensys can give you a list of the devices with a particular vulnerability.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Search results&nbsp;for Acunetix(http://testphp.vulnweb.com/) in Censys.io (Screenshot- 521)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Search results for Altoro mutual(http://demo.testfire.net//) in Censys.io (Screenshot- 520)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>--</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Overview of Censys.io IoT Search Engine</li>\r\n	<li>Searching particular applications&nbsp;in Censys.io</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-05-10', '2021-05-10', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-05-23 04:07:53', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(159, 146, 42, '<p>A JSON report containing&nbsp;IP addresses of the hosts&nbsp;for Acunetix(http://testphp.vulnweb.com/) in Censys.io- (Screenshot- 522, 523)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A JSON report containing hosts per City for&nbsp;Acunetix(http://testphp.vulnweb.com/) in Censys.io- (Screenshot- 524, 525)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A JSON report containing IP Addresses of the hosts for&nbsp;Altoro mutual (http://demo.testfire.net//)&nbsp;in Censys.io (Screenshot- 526, 527)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A JSON report containing hosts per Country for&nbsp;Altoro mutual(http://demo.testfire.net//) in Censys.io- (528, 529)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We can create reports&nbsp;in different ways for our search results in Censys.io as per our requirements.</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Creating reports in Censys for&nbsp;IP addresses of hosts using a particular web application.</li>\r\n	<li>Creating reports as per the City/Country&nbsp;of the hosts using a particular web application.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-05-23', '2021-05-23', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-05-23 11:19:18', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(160, 147, 42, '<p><strong>The Google Hacking Database:</strong><br />\r\nThe Google Hacking Database (GHDB) is a compendium of Google hacking search terms that have been found to reveal sensitive data exposed by vulnerable servers and web applications.<br />\r\nThe GHDB was launched to serve penetration testers. In 2010, Long turned the database over to Offensive Security and it became part of exploit-db.com.<br />\r\nIt was also expanded to include not only the Google search engine but also other search engines like Microsoft&rsquo;s Bing as well as other repositories such as GitHub.<br />\r\nThe Vulnerabilities of websites/servers are uploaded in GHDB by different Pentesters and Security researchers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Some of the categories of search engine query in the GHDB include:</strong><br />\r\nProduct-specific advisories<br />\r\nError messages that contain sensitive information such as directory paths<br />\r\nFiles with sensitive data, passwords, and user names<br />\r\nSensitive online shopping data<br />\r\nDetailed information about web servers</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Home page of GHDB:</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It Contains Dorks(Search query which addresses vulnerabilities), Date added, Vulnerability Category, and Author(person who added Dork).&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 530)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Overview of Google Hacking Database</li>\r\n	<li>Search query&nbsp;Categories&nbsp;in GHDB</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-05-23', '2021-05-23', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-05-23 17:07:41', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(161, 148, 42, '<p><strong>Exploit Database:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Exploit database contains different downloadable Exploits for Vulnerabilities Identified on various platforms by different Pentesters or Security researchers</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Home Page of Exploit Database:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Exploit Database site consists of Downloadable Exploits, Vulnerable Applications, Type of the Exploit, Vulnerable Platform on which vulnerability was found, and the person who identified them.<em> (Screenshot- 535)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>We can also search for the Platforms (Eg: Windows, which shows the Exploits for Windows for the vulnerabilities identified)<em> (Screenshot- 536),&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Exploit Database overview</li>\r\n	<li>Its Contents and Downloadable files</li>\r\n	<li>Using search for finding Exploits of particular types.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-05-24', '2021-05-24', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-05-24 07:35:03', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(162, 149, 42, '<p><strong>Google Hacking Database:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Vulnerabilities of websites/servers are uploaded in GHDB by different Pentesters and Security researchers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Home page of GHDB:</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It Contains Dorks(Search query which addresses vulnerabilities), Date added, Vulnerability Category, and Author(person who added Dork).&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 530)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Searching for unprotected webcams</strong> from Quick search in Exploit-db&nbsp;GHDB&nbsp; &nbsp; <em>(Screenshot- 531)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Open a Webcam from the Dorks list&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot-532)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Follow the link, Opening it in the new tab- we can view the camera capturing video <em>(Screenshot- 533)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Accesing Vulnerabilities reported by different Pentesters and Security researchers in GHDB.</li>\r\n	<li>Using Search in Google Hacking Database.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-05-23', '2021-05-23', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-05-23 18:49:40', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(163, 150, 42, '<p>We can find the Metasploit: The Penetration Tester&#39;s Guide PDF using Google Hacking&nbsp;with the Search Operators.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Search-<strong> intext:metasploit filetype:pdf &quot;The Penetration Tester&#39;s Guide&quot;</strong>&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 537)&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Metasploit: The Penetration Tester&#39;s Guide PDF file is found <em>(Screenshot- 538)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Using Google Hacking with Search Operators</li>\r\n	<li>Finding PDF File of Metasploit: The Penetration Tester&#39;s Guide</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-05-24', '2021-05-24', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-05-24 08:41:28', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(164, 151, 42, '<p>An XLS file containing a bunch of Gmail Usernames can be found using Google Search Operators&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 539)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Search text:&nbsp;<strong>intext:username filetype:xls &quot;gmail&quot;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(Screenshot- 540)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This results in the sites containing XLS containing Username in the File and With the Keyword&nbsp;&#39;gmail&#39;</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Searching for XLS file containing a bunch of Gmail usernames</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-05-24', '2021-05-24', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-05-24 09:25:34', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
