(169, 156, 42, '<p><strong>Ansible:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ansible is an open-source software provisioning, configuration management, and application-deployment tool enabling infrastructure as code.<br />\r\nIt runs on many Unix-like systems and can configure both Unix-like systems as well as Microsoft Windows.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is a Push type configuration tool i.e. Server pushes Configuration and Commands to the&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is Agentless i.e. There is no need for any special software to be installed on the Client&#39;s system.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It connects over SSH and Runs commands.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It uses Playbook. An Ansible playbook is a blueprint of automation tasks. These tasks are complex IT actions executed with limited or no human involvement.<br />\r\nAnsible playbooks are executed on a set, group, or classification of hosts, which together make up an Ansible inventory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Creating Playbook:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The playbook is a YML file that defines tasks to be executed.<br />\r\nTo create one, execute the command in the system with Ansible Installed- &#39;vi check_nmap.yml&#39;<br />\r\nPress &#39;i&#39; for editing the newly created yml file<br />\r\nEntering tasks to be executed in yml syntax:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>---<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp;-name: check_nmap<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; hosts: all<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; tasks:<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; -name:Install nmap<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;apt:<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;name:nmap<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;state:present</strong><br />\r\nSave and run the Playbook to install nmap. Execute the Playbook by the using command:<br />\r\n&#39;ansible-playbook check_nmap.yml&#39;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Installing Symantec Endpoint Protection Remotely:</strong><br />\r\n<strong>Steps:</strong><br />\r\n<strong>(1)</strong>&nbsp;Log in to the Symantec Endpoint Protection Manager with Administrative credentials (Screenshot- 502)<br />\r\n<strong>(2)</strong> Access the Dashboard open the Clients module from the menu (Screenshot- 503)<br />\r\n<strong>(3)</strong> From the tasks menu in the Clients module, Click on &#39;Install a Client&#39;&nbsp;<br />\r\n<strong>(4)</strong> Select the Deployment type whether to deploy New package or an Existing Package <em>(Screenshot- 504)</em><br />\r\n<strong>(5)</strong> If Selected New package deployment from the previous options, Select the packages and feature sets to be installed from the dropdown lists <em>(Screenshot- 506)</em><br />\r\n<strong>(6)</strong> In the next window, select the &#39;Remote Push&#39; option and click next.&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 507)</em><br />\r\n<strong>(7)</strong> Select the Network to which you want to deploy Endpoint Protection for all the Clients connected to it.&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 508)</em><br />\r\n<strong>(8)</strong> We can also enter the IP address of a particular machine for deploying Endpoint Protection.&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 510, 511)</em><br />\r\n<strong>(9)</strong> Administrator credentials of the Client&#39;s system are to be entered. <em>(Screenshot- 512)</em><br />\r\n<strong>(10)</strong> The package setup is complete and we get the information of systems to which we are going to deploy Endpoint Protection. Click on &#39;Send&#39; to deploy.&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 514)</em><br />\r\n<strong>(11)</strong> Deployment is Successful and We can manage the new clients from the Clients module in Symantec Endpoint Protection Manager. <em>(Screenshot- 516, 517)</em><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Overview of Ansible</li>\r\n	<li>Installing a software tool using Ansible</li>\r\n	<li>Deploying Symantec Endpoint Protection Remotely</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-05-22', '2021-05-22', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-05-22 16:10:33', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(170, 157, 42, '<p><strong>Group Policy</strong> is a feature of Windows that facilitates a wide variety of advanced settings that network administrators can use to control the working environment of users and computer accounts in Active Directory.<br />\r\nIt essentially provides a centralized place for administrators to manage and configure operating systems, applications, and users&rsquo; settings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We can open the Group Policy Editor by typing &#39;gpedit.msc&#39; in the Command Prompt or Run feature(Windows+R).&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot-304)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>In the Group Policy Editor</strong>, we have Two fields namely: (1) Computer Configuration and (2) User Configuration</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(1) Computer Configuration</strong> defines Computer Settings applied before a user logs in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For Example, If we want to prevent a user from logging in to Windows:<br />\r\nSteps: <strong>(i)</strong> In the Group Policy Editor access dropdowns- Computer configuration &gt; Windows settings &gt; Security settings&gt; Local policies &gt; User rights assignment.&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 301)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(ii)</strong> Click on the User rights assignment and search for the &#39;Deny log on locally&#39;&nbsp;policy on the Right part of the window.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(iii)</strong> Open the&nbsp;&#39;Deny log on locally&#39; policy by double-clicking on the name. From the new window opened click on the &#39;Add user or group&#39; button to add the required user for restricting login.&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 305)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(iv)</strong> Enter the user name and click on check names and once the user name is loaded, Apply the settings. <em>(Screenshot- 305,303)</em>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<strong>(2) User Configuration</strong> defines Computer Settings applies when the user logs in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For Example, If we want to prevent a user from accessing Control Panel:<br />\r\nSteps: <strong>(i)</strong> In the Group Policy Editor access dropdowns- User Configuration &gt; Administrative Templates &gt; Control Panel <em>(Screenshot- 496)</em>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(ii)</strong> Click on the Control panel and search for the &#39;Prohibit access to Control panel and PC settings&#39; in the right part of the window. <em>(Screenshot- 497)&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(iii)</strong> Open it by double-clicking on its name and change the settings to &#39;Enable&#39; and apply the settings. <em>(Screenshot- 498)</em></p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Working with Group Policy Editor</li>\r\n	<li>Preventing a user from logging in to the Windows</li>\r\n	<li>Restricting a user from accessing Control Panel and PC Settings</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-05-20', '2021-05-20', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-05-21 09:50:44', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(171, 158, 42, '<p>The Server Message Block (SMB) is a network protocol that enables users to communicate with remote computers and servers to use their resources or share, open, and edit files. It&rsquo;s also referred to as the server/client protocol, as the server has a resource that it can share with the client.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like any network file sharing protocol, SMB needs network ports to communicate with other systems. Originally, it used port 139 that allowed computers to communicate on the same network. But since Windows 2000, SMB uses port 445 and the TCP network protocol to &ldquo;talk&rdquo; to other computers over the internet.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The SMB protocol creates a connection between the server and the client by sending multiple request-response messages back and forth.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Let&rsquo;s say that the printer in our office is connected to the receptionists&rsquo; PC. If you want to print a document, your computer (the client) sends the receptionists&rsquo; computer (the server) a request to print it and uses the SMB protocol to do it. The server will then send back a response, stating that the file is queued, printed, or that the printer ran out of ink and is unable to perform the task.</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Overview of SMB Protocol</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-05-21', '2021-05-21', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-06-02 19:41:31', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(172, 159, 42, '<p><strong>SMBv1:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Back in the 1980s-90s IBM and Microsoft were working on implementations of SMB to improve and build upon the protocol.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Microsoft&nbsp;added a bunch of features, such as support for larger files and direct connections over port 445.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SMBv1 was deprecated in 2013 and is no longer installed by default on Windows Server 2016. There are a handful of vulnerabilities that exist within SMBv1, most of which allow for remote code execution on the target host.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most of these vulnerabilities have a patch available, but more often than not, SMBv1 can be completely disabled. Unless you have legacy systems in your environment that require SMBv1 (Windows XP) or legacy applications that rely on it, you&rsquo;ll most likely not affect anything by disabling it across your organization.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>SMBv2:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>SMBv2 was introduced in Windows Vista, circa 2006 by Microsoft. With the new version of SMB, came performance improvements and new features, such as support for symbolic links.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>SMBv3:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>SMBv3 was introduced with Windows 8 and Windows Server 2012, with this new version, came more performance improvements and security enhancements, such as end-to-end encryption.</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Overview of SMB Versions SMB V1, V2 and V3.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-06-16', '2021-06-16', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-06-16 17:10:06', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(173, 160, 42, '<p>Vulnerabilities:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>SMB V1</strong>: There are a handful of vulnerabilities that exist within SMBv1, most of which allow for remote code execution on the target host.<br />\r\nEternalBlue is the exploit named after exploiting the vulnerability.<br />\r\nEternalBlue exists because SMBv1 is not able to handle specific packets crafted by a remote attacker, leading to remote code execution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>SMB V2</strong>: Microsoft Windows SMB2 &#39;_Smb2ValidateProviderCallback()&#39; Vulnerability . An attacker can exploit this flaw to disable the remote host or to execute arbitrary code on it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>SMB V3</strong>: vulnerability is actually the one identified as CVE-2020-0796 and has characteristics of worms. This vulnerability exists in the way the Microsoft SMBv3 protocol handles certain requests.<br />\r\nSince Windows 10 v1709 and Windows Server v1803, Microsoft randomizes memory allocation of processes. This randomization significantly increases the difficulty of successful exploitation of memory corruption vulnerabilities such CVE-2020-0796.</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Critical Vulnerabilities in different SMB Versions.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-06-25', '2021-06-25', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-06-25 06:31:57', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(174, 161, 42, '<p><strong>Installations did for the task to be accomplished:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>- Installed VMware<br />\r\n- Installed Windows Server 2019 in VMware using the ISO file<br />\r\n- Installed Windows ENT in VMware using the ISO file<br />\r\n- Installed Kali Linux in VMware using ISO file</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Promoted Windows Server to Domain Controller: (Screenshot-634)<br />\r\nSteps:</strong><br />\r\n- Change your Server IP to static IP and Preferred DNS with the same IP address<br />\r\n- Open the Server Manager in the Windows server<br />\r\n- From the dashboard click on Manage from the top right of the window and choose Add roles and features to continue<br />\r\n- You will get Add roles and features Wizard dialogue box, here just click the Next button.<br />\r\n- In the next window in the server roles dialogue box, tick the &quot;Active Directory Domain Services&quot; box<br />\r\n- On clicking the Add-Features button the installation will start<br />\r\n- Open your Server Dashboard, click on the yellow exclamation mark to open the drop menu.. here you have to click Promote this server to a domain controller link.<br />\r\n- Click Add a new forest button. On the Root domain name, type your new domain name.<br />\r\n- Click next for the review options dialog boxes and you can see &ldquo;All prerequisite check passed successfully. Click &quot;install&quot; to begin the installation. Next, click the Install button.<br />\r\n- The Server will auto reboot. After the reboot, you now can log in as a Domain Administrator.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Configuring the Virtual machines( Kali Linux, Windows Enterprise, Windows Server 2019) on the Same Network:</strong><br />\r\n- Open each VM&#39;s Settings from the VMware Dashboard and Change the Network Settings from the default NAT Network to Bridged Network. <em>(Screenshot- 636)</em><br />\r\n- Change the IP Addresses of all the Three VMs to Static IP<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp;I&#39;ve configured as follows:<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp;For Windows Server 2019- 192.168.10.100 <em>(Screenshot- 638)</em><br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp;For Kali Linux- 192.168.10.101 <em>(Screenshot- 639)</em><br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp;For Windows Enterprise- 192.168.10.102 <em>(Screenshot- 637)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>To Check whether the Virtual Machines are on the Same Network, Try Pining the other two machines from one machine:</strong><br />\r\nPinging Kali Linux(192.168.10.101) and Windows Enterprise(192.168.10.102) from Windows Server 2019 <em>(Screenshot- 642)</em><br />\r\nPinging Windows Server 2019(192.168.10.100) and Windows Enterprise(192.168.10.102) from the Kali Linux <em>(Screenshot- 641)</em><br />\r\nPinging Kali Linux(192.168.10.101) and Windows Server 2019(192.168.10.100) from Windows Enterprise <em>(Screenshot- 640)</em></p>\r\n', '<p>Error - while configuring Kali Linux Ip to Static IP&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Host Not reachable error while pinging</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Installing Windows Server 2019 on Vmware</li>\r\n	<li>Installing WIndows Enterprise</li>\r\n	<li>Promoting Windows Server to Domain Controller</li>\r\n	<li>Configuring VM&#39;s to Static IP Address</li>\r\n	<li>Configuring the three VM&#39;s on the Same Network</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-07-02', '2021-07-06', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-07-06 13:24:01', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(175, 162, 42, '<p>To check the IP Address of the Windows Enterprise Version, Open the Command Prompt and execute the command &quot;ipconfig&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(Screenshot- 638)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>To change the IP address to static: Steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Open the Network Sharing centre and click on the Ethernet link, and click on the Properties.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Select the Internet Protocol Version 4(IPv4)&nbsp;and open its properties.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Enter the custom IP address and the preferred DNS Server.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Click on Apply the Settings and Close the windows</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To check whether the IP Address is updated repeat the same command execution mentioned above in Command Prompt.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '', '2021-07-05', '2021-07-06', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-07-07 14:17:52', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N');
