(176, 163, 42, '<p>Scanning Domain Controller- Windows Server 2019 for Open ports: <em>(Screenshot- 644)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Open the Command Prompt in the Windows Server and run the command -</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>netstat -aon | find /i &quot;listening&quot;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here &#39;a&#39; - For displaying all the connections and Open ports</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;o&#39; - For displaying Owning process ID</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;n&#39; - For displaying ports and addresses in Numerical form&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>On running &#39;netstat -aon&#39; command, The ports are being listed infinitely.</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Scanning for Open ports using Command Prompt</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-07-07', '2021-07-07', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-07-07 19:40:01', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(177, 164, 42, '<p>By default, the server listens on TCP port 3389 and UDP port 3389. Microsoft currently refers to their official RDP client software as <strong>Remote Desktop Connection.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>As port 3389 is open which allows the remote desktop connection,&nbsp;hence its could be the entry point to attack the machine and gain admin access to it.</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Port analyzing</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-07-21', '2021-07-21', 1, '4', 'Y', 0, '2021-07-29 06:57:32', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(178, 165, 42, '<p>By default, the server listens on TCP port 3389 and UDP port 3389. Microsoft currently refers to their official RDP client software as <strong>Remote Desktop Connection</strong>, formerly &quot;Terminal Services Client&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We can enable port 3389 by following the steps below:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(1) Open the ControlPanel &gt; Programs and Features &gt; Turn windows features on or off</p>\r\n\r\n<p>search and mark&nbsp;&quot;Telnet client&quot; and click on the &#39;Apply&#39; button</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(2) Navigate to the &quot;System and Security&quot; in the Control panel and open the &quot;Remote Settings&quot; from the left part of the window.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(3) Select the dialogue box &quot;Allow remote connections to this computer&quot; and click on the &#39;Apply&#39; button and save.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(4) Open the Control panel and to enable the Port 3389,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Run the command &quot;telnet 127.0.0.1 3389&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here, 127.0.0.1 is the Localhost, and 3389 is the RDP Port</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Overview and Use of port 3389</li>\r\n	<li>Enabling the 3389 port for Remote connection</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-07-13', '2021-07-13', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-07-13 11:05:07', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(179, 166, 42, '<p>A port is an endpoint to a logical connection and the way a client program specifies a specific server program on a node. There are more than 60,000 ports.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>TCP port 58</strong> uses Transmission Control Protocol and it guarantees the delivery of data packets in the same order in which they were sent.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UDP port 58</strong> uses the Datagram Protocol and it provides an unreliable service. The datagrams may arrive duplicated, missing, or out of order without notice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TCP port 58 provides a guaranteed communication than UDP port 58.</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Overview and USe of Port 58</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-07-12', '2021-07-13', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-07-13 11:47:01', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(180, 167, 42, '<p><strong>Bruteforcing RDP port of remote machine:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>We have the Remote Windows machine with a known IP Address and Open RDP port.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And Kali Linux as our Host system.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Steps</strong>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>1</strong>) Firstly we need to make sure that the RDP port i.e, 3389 is open on the remote windows machine. This can be done using Nmap scan, Using the command to scan the open ports - &#39;namp -sV &lt;IPAddress of the machine&gt;&#39; and in the results, the port number and its state can be viewed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>2</strong>) To perform brute-forcing we are using the tool named Hydra which is inbuilt in the Kali Linux. We need two text files, one is a probable user&nbsp;list and a probable password list.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>3</strong>) Create the user and the password lists by using the commands &#39;nano user.txt&#39; and &#39;nano pass.txt&#39; in the Terminal and Enter the list of some probable usernames and passwords that are to be provided to Hydra for carrying out&nbsp;brute force&nbsp;attack.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>4</strong>) After the successful creation of the user and password lists, Its time to Initiate the brute force attack by providing the IP Address of the remote machine along with the user and password lists.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>5</strong>) Now, execute the command &#39;hydra -L user.txt -P pass.txt &lt;IPAddress&gt; rdp&#39; to initiate the attack.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The attack will take time as it will be checking with the possible usernames and passwords from the lists.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>6</strong>) If the attack was successful a confirmation message will be displayed with the actual username and password as</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[3389][rdp] host: 10.0.2.15 &nbsp; login: Gursharan &nbsp; password: Gursharan91<br />\r\n1 of 1 target successfully completed, 1 valid password found</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(Screenshot- 756)</em></p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Learned how to perform Brute forcing attack to the remote machine RDP port.</li>\r\n	<li>Using Hydra and Nmap</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-08-25', '2021-08-26', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-08-26 20:01:51', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(181, 168, 42, '<p><strong>Creating Probable&nbsp;Username&nbsp;list and Probable&nbsp;Password&nbsp;list:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Open the Terminal of the host Kali Linux</li>\r\n	<li>To create the user and the password lists, execute&nbsp;the commands &#39;nano user.txt&#39; and &#39;nano pass.txt&#39; and enter the probable values in both the lists respectively.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Usernames list: <em>Screenshot-785</em>, and Passwords list: <em>Screenshot-786</em>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Creating lists of probable Usernames and Passwords that are used to brute force a machine remotely in further tasks.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-08-31', '2021-09-01', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-09-01 15:47:19', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(182, 169, 42, '<p>The probable username and password lists created in the previous task i.e, user.txt and pass.txt files <em>(Screenshots- 785, 786)&nbsp;</em>should contain the actual username and password of a remote machine at random places in the list. Since we are practicing brute force attacks, it is suggested to use the known machines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We have added the actual username and password of the target Windows Machine present on the same network as our host Kali&nbsp;machine. <em>(Screenshot- 790)</em></p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '', '', '2021-09-01', '2021-09-01', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-09-01 15:59:55', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(183, 170, 42, '<p><strong>Bruteforcing RDP port of remote machine:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>We have the Remote Windows machine with a known IP Address and Open RDP port.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And Kali Linux as our Host system. Both the machines are on the same network <em>(Screenshot- 783)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Steps</strong>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>1</strong>) Firstly we need to make sure that the RDP port i.e, 3389 is open on the remote windows machine. This can be done using Nmap scan, Using the command to scan the open ports - &#39;namp -sV &#39; and in the results, the port number and its state can be viewed. <em>(Screenshot-784)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>2</strong>) To perform brute-forcing we are using the tool named Hydra which is inbuilt in the Kali Linux. The Hydra tool requires&nbsp;two text files, one is a probable user&nbsp;list and a probable password list. which were created previously <em>(Screenshots- 785, 786)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>3</strong>) As User and Password lists are ready, It&#39;s time to Initiate the brute force attack by providing Hydra with the IP Address of the remote machine along with the user and password lists.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>4</strong>)&nbsp;Execute the command &#39;hydra -L user.txt -P pass.txt &lt;Ipaddress&gt;&nbsp;rdp&#39; to initiate the attack.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The attack will take time as it will be checking with all the possible combinations of usernames and passwords from the lists.&nbsp;<em>(Screenshots- 787)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>5</strong>) If the attack is successful a confirmation message will be displayed with the actual username and password as</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[3389][rdp] host: 10.0.2.15 &nbsp; login: Gursharan &nbsp; password: Gursharan91<br />\r\n1 of 1 target successfully completed, 1 valid password found</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(Screenshots- 787)</em></p>\r\n', '', '<ul>\r\n	<li>How to perform a Brute forcing attack to the remote machine&#39;s RDP port.</li>\r\n	<li>Using Hydra and Nmap tools</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-09-01', '2021-09-01', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-09-01 16:11:49', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(184, 171, 42, '<p>As in the last Brute force attack,&nbsp;we&nbsp;got&nbsp;the login creds of the user present on Windows machine. The results were displayed as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[3389][rdp] host: 10.0.2.15 &nbsp; login: Gursharan &nbsp; password: Gursharan91<br />\r\n1 of 1 target successfully completed, 1 valid password found&nbsp;<em>(Screenshots- 787)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Trying to login to the RDP of the remote machine with the credentials found:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(1) Open the Kali Linux terminal and make sure both the machines are on the same network(Try pinging).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(2) We are using &#39;rdesktop&#39; tool for&nbsp;connecting to the RDP of ther remote windows machine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(3) Now execute the following command in the Kali Linux terminal:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;rdesktop -u Gursharan -p Gursharan192 10.0.2.15&#39;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>and&nbsp;in a new window, the remote access to the windows machine will be opened.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(Screenshot- 801)</em></p>\r\n', '<p>Error -&#39;Connection reset by peer&#39; Update: Resolved</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Connecting to RDP using the rdesktop.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-09-08', '2021-09-08', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-09-08 07:32:37', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(185, 172, 42, '<p>As the new RDP connection was made using the rdesktop with the commands:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;rdesktop -u Gursharan -p Gursharan192 10.0.2.15&#39;&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 801)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now we are tyring to access the cmd of Remote Windows machine from Kali Linux with Administrator privileges:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Press Win+R button and run &#39;cmd&#39;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And the cmd is accessible&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 802)</em></p>\r\n', '', '', '', '2021-09-02', '2021-09-02', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-09-08 07:39:13', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(186, 173, 42, '<p><strong>Airmon-ng</strong>&nbsp;is included in the Aircrack-ng package and is used to enable and disable monitor mode on wireless interfaces. It may also be used to go back from monitor mode to managed mode.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Killing the interfering processes using&nbsp;Airmon-ng:<em> (Screenshot- 800)</em></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A number of processes can interfere with Airmon-ng, So to start using Airmon-ng it is suggested to end those&nbsp;processes. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(1)&nbsp;</strong>Checking if there are interfering processes:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Command:</em>&nbsp;airmon-ng check</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(2)</strong> Killing the processes found in the above scanning:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Command:</em>&nbsp;airmon-ng check &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Enabling Monitor mode using Airmon-ng:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>By enabling monitor mode on a wireless network interface, A new interface will be created which possesses monitor mode turned on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(1)&nbsp;</strong>Check for the wireless network interfaces present on the machine having monitor mode feature:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Command</em>:&nbsp;iwconfig <em>(Screenshot- 800)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This will display all the network interfaces on the system. Note the interface name supporting&nbsp;the monitor mode feature. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(2)</strong>&nbsp;Starting the monitor mode for a particular interface:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Command:</em>&nbsp;airmon-ng start &lt;interface_name&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Disabling Monitor mode using Airmon-ng:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>To disable the Monitor mode on a particular interface execute the command:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>airmon-ng stop &lt;Interface_name&gt;</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Overview of Airmon-ng</li>\r\n	<li>Enabling and Disabling monitor mode using Airmon-ng for wireless interfaces</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-09-07', '2021-09-07', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-09-07 10:15:42', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(187, 174, 42, '<p>Other than Aircrack-ng (Previous task) there are different tools that can be used in&nbsp;wifi/wireless attacking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Following are the different such tools:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>AirSnort:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>AirSnort is free WiFi hacking software that captures the packets and tries to decrypt the keys. The monitoring is done in promiscuous mode and records enough packets to reliably decrypt the key. It is a simple tool and supports both Windows and Linux platforms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>AirSnort requires a potentially large amount of data to be gathered before the attack is successful. AirSnort also comes with a largely unknown utility that will perform a dictionary attack on a relatively tiny sampling of network traffic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Kismet:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kismet is a wireless network sniffer that works for Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, software-defined Radio (SDR) and other wireless protocols. It passively collects packets being broadcast in its vicinity and analyzes them to detect even hidden Wi-Fi networks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kismet is supported on all operating systems (using WSL on Windows) and is actively supported.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Wifiphisher:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wifiphisher is a tool designed to perform&nbsp;man-in-the-middle attacks&nbsp;by exploiting Wi-Fi association. By convincing wireless users to connect to the rogue access point, Wifiphisher provides an attacker with the ability to intercept and monitor or modify their wireless traffic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wifiphisher also enables an attacker to launch web phishing attacks. These can be used to collect user credentials for third-party sites or Wi-Fi network credentials. Additionally, Wifiphisher is designed to be modular, enabling advanced users to write custom code to expand its capabilities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CoWPAtty:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>CoWPAtty is an automated dictionary attack tool for WPA-PSK. It runs on Linux OS. This program has a command-line interface and runs on a word list that contains the password to use in the attack.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Using the tool is simple, but it is slow. That&rsquo;s because the hash uses PBKDF2 with 4096 iterations to generate a potential passphrase from a network SSID and password. Since each calculation of PBKDF takes time, this makes a brute force password guessing attack very slow.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, CoWPAtty does have a rainbow table designed to mitigate this issue. Since many routers have common SSIDs, pre-computed tables have been generated for these SSIDs and common passwords. If the target network is one of these, testing it against the precomputed dictionary is much faster.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>AirJack:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>AirJack is a Wi-Fi 802.11 packet injection tool. This wireless cracking tool is very useful in injecting forged packets and taking a network down via a denial of service attack. This tool can also be used for a man-in-the-middle attack on the network.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Airgeddon:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Airgeddon is designed to be an all-in-one tool for security analysis of wireless networks. To accomplish this, it integrates several existing tools and provides a single command-line interface for all of them. This helps to reduce the complexity of performing Wi-Fi security audits because Airgeddon&rsquo;s CLI walks you through the process and handles interactions with all of the underlying tools.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CloudCracker:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>CloudCracker is an online password cracking tool for cracking WPA-protected Wi-Fi networks. This tool can also be used to crack different password hashes. Just upload the handshake file, enter the network name, and start the tool. This tool has a huge dictionary of around 300 million words to perform attacks.</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Getting introduced to different wifi attacking tools.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-10-26', '2021-10-27', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-10-27 10:34:28', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(188, 175, 42, '<h2><strong>Dictionary Attacks:</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;AirSnort:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>AirSnort is free WiFi hacking software that captures the packets and tries to decrypt the keys. The monitoring is done in promiscuous mode and records enough packets to reliably decrypt the key. It is a simple tool and supports both Windows and Linux platforms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>AirSnort requires a potentially large amount of data to be gathered before the attack is successful. AirSnort also comes with a largely unknown utility that will perform a dictionary attack on a relatively tiny sampling of network traffic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CoWPAtty:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>CoWPAtty is an automated dictionary attack tool for WPA-PSK. It runs on Linux OS. This program has a command-line interface and runs on a word list that contains the password to use in the attack.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Using the tool is simple, but it is slow. That&rsquo;s because the hash uses PBKDF2 with 4096 iterations to generate a potential passphrase from a network SSID and password. Since each calculation of PBKDF takes time, this makes a brute force password guessing attack very slow.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CloudCracker:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>CloudCracker is an online password cracking tool for cracking WPA-protected Wi-Fi networks. This tool can also be used to crack different password hashes. Just upload the handshake file, enter the network name, and start the tool. This tool has a huge dictionary of around 300 million words to perform attacks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Wireless/Wifi Sniffing:</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Kismet</strong>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kismet is a wireless network sniffer that works for Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, software-defined Radio (SDR) and other wireless protocols. It passively collects packets being broadcast in its vicinity and analyzes them to detect even hidden Wi-Fi networks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kismet is supported on all operating systems (using WSL on Windows) and is actively supported.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Airgeddon:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Airgeddon is designed to be an all-in-one tool for security analysis of wireless networks. To accomplish this, it integrates several existing tools and provides a single command-line interface for all of them. This helps to reduce the complexity of performing Wi-Fi security audits because Airgeddon&rsquo;s CLI walks you through the process and handles interactions with all of the underlying tools.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Phishing Attacks:</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Wifiphisher:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wifiphisher is a tool designed to perform&nbsp;man-in-the-middle attacks&nbsp;by exploiting Wi-Fi association. By convincing wireless users to connect to the rogue access point, Wifiphisher provides an attacker with the ability to intercept and monitor or modify their wireless traffic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wifiphisher also enables an attacker to launch web phishing attacks. These can be used to collect user credentials for third-party sites or Wi-Fi network credentials. Additionally, Wifiphisher is designed to be modular, enabling advanced users to write custom code to expand its capabilities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Packet Injection attacks:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>AirJack:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>AirJack is a Wi-Fi 802.11 packet injection tool. This wireless cracking tool is very useful in injecting forged packets and taking a network down via a denial of service attack. This tool can also be used for a man-in-the-middle attack on the network.</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Different types of wireless/wifi attacks and tools associated with them.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-10-27', '2021-10-27', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-10-27 11:00:40', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(189, 176, 42, '<p>Applications that use&nbsp;SNMP(Simple Network Management Protocol)&nbsp;as a source of data are very popular way of keeping tabs on what is running on your network. Most of these types of applications can also send alerts when things go down or get too busy. But what if you want to get more information about what is happening on your network? &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In my experience packet or flow capture is the next logical upgrade to SNMP. Packet capture allows you to take a mirror image of network packets as they move through a network. Flow data usually contains a summary of what connections are been setup on a network. Both are really useful technologies for troubleshooting and finding out what is happening on a network.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>New_Words:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DPI- Deep Packet Inspection</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SNMP- Simple Network Management Protocol</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Flow data</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most routers and switches which operate at Network layer of the OSI model&nbsp;will have flow export options. There are many flow standards around and they include NetFlow, sFlow and IPFIX. You just need to install a flow connector which can process whatever flow standard your network equipment uses. &nbsp;Flow based analysis can be a great way to find out what traffic is traversing across certain parts of your network.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pros:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Easy to setup on devices which operate at layer 3</li>\r\n	<li>No cabling required</li>\r\n	<li>No software clients or agents needed on end user systems</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Cons:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>No flow options on some switches</li>\r\n	<li>Lacks detail when you want to troubleshoot a problem</li>\r\n	<li>Not ideal for monitoring at the edge of your network where&nbsp;applications piggy back on other protocols</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Packet capture</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Packet capture&nbsp;involves capturing a mirror image of network packets as they move through a network. Most switches allow for the setup of mirror ports which do not impact network performance. Typically, a deep packet inspection (DPI) application is connected to a mirror port and certain information is extracted from the packets so you can find out what is happening on your network. DPI solutions range from free stuff like&nbsp;Wireshark&nbsp;to commercial applications which take the hard work out of the analysis.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pros:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Better for analysis of application and user behaviour.&nbsp; Detect bad vs. good use of bandwidth</li>\r\n	<li>Ideal for monitoring important applications, servers or Internet connections where low level information is critical</li>\r\n	<li>You get a lot more &lsquo;names&rsquo;. Application, file, website and host names.</li>\r\n	<li>No software clients or agents needed on end user systems</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cons:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>You need to connect cables between mirror ports and your DPI application</li>\r\n	<li>Need to watch that mirror ports don&rsquo;t get overloaded on busy networks</li>\r\n	<li>Free tools may need a high level of technical expertise to interpret the output</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>So, which technology should you leverage on your network? In some cases the answer is both. Flow analysis can be great if you have a lot of WAN links and need an easy way to get top level visibility without the need for cables. Packet capture will give you a lot more detail at certain points on your network. A combination of both can mean you&nbsp;detect bandwidth hogs&nbsp;easier, as well as reporting on what applications are in use and by whom.</p>\r\n', '', '<p>Understanding &nbsp;Flow data and&nbsp;Packet data</p>\r\n', '', '2021-10-27', '2021-10-31', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-10-31 15:17:06', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
