(255, 224, 42, '<p>Installed Ubuntu Server 20.04.2 LTS</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Steps to do so:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(1)</strong> Download the ISO file for Ubuntu Server 20.04.2 from Ubuntu.com</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(2)</strong> Setup a&nbsp;New Virtual machine for Ubuntu Server in the Virtual box (including loading of ISO file)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(3)&nbsp;</strong>Start the Virtual machine and the Installation setup of Ubuntu will be loaded. Select the language and keyboard type. (Screenshot- 487) Use Enter to select.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(4)</strong> The next window will be of Guided Storage Configuration. Select Use the entire disk option by using Tab and Space from the keyboard. (Screenshot- 488). Hit Enter and Confirm the action (Screenshot- 489).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(5)&nbsp;</strong>The next window will be of SSH setup installation. Select the Install OpenSSH server using space and press enter. This will install the OpenSSH server by default. (Screenshot- 490)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(6)&nbsp;</strong>The Installation of the kernel&nbsp;will begin (Screenshot- 491) and <strong>You encounter an Error here&nbsp;</strong>stating &#39;failed unmounting /cdrom&#39;. (Screenshot- 492)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To resolve this error get back to the Virtual Box dashboard and get into the settings of the Ubuntu Server VM being installed and remove the ISO file from Storage &gt; Control: IDE which we loaded previously.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(7) </strong>Open back the VM and press Enter and the Installation process will continue. (Screenshot- 493)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(8)</strong> Enter the Username and Password to Login into the Ubuntu Server (Screenshot- 494, 495)</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Installation of Ubuntu Server&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-06-15', '2021-06-15', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-06-15 10:04:22', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(256, 225, 42, '<p>The key difference between regular Ubuntu and Ubuntu Core is the underlying architecture of the system. Traditional Linux distributions rely mostly on traditional package system- &#39;deb&#39; in Ubuntu&#39;s case&nbsp;<br />\r\nwhile Ubuntu Core relies almost entirely on Canonical&#39;s relatively new snap package format.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Ubuntu Core</strong> runs a new breed of super-secure, remotely upgradeable Linux app packages known as &#39;Snaps&#39;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here: Snap is a software package and deployment system that uses self-contained packages called snaps to deliver software to users.<br />\r\nWhile APT mostly obtains packages from a distribution&#39;s official repositories, Snap enables developers to deliver their apps directly to users via the Snap Store.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ubuntu core is also called as Ubuntu for IoT and Embedded systems<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\nFeatures of Ubuntu Core:&nbsp;<br />\r\nSecured and cryptographically stronger booting sequence.<br />\r\nFull disk encryption.<br />\r\nCan be used for Embedded, IoT, Robotics, Industrial and Automotive applications.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Ubuntu Server</strong> is a server operating system developed by Canonical and open source programmers around the world, that works with nearly any hardware or virtualization platform.<br />\r\nIt can serve up websites, file shares, and containers, as well as expand your company offerings with cloud presence.</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Overview of Ubuntu Core</li>\r\n	<li>Overview of Ubuntu Server</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-06-15', '2021-06-15', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-06-15 13:13:34', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(257, 226, 42, '<p>As per the Ubuntu official website, Ubuntu Core is none other than the Ubuntu Server. Attached is the reference to the above statement from Ubuntu.com. (Screenshot- 594, 593)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Installing the Ubuntu Server:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Installed Ubuntu Server 20.04.2 LTS</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Steps to do so:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(1)</strong> Download the ISO file for Ubuntu Server 20.04.2 from Ubuntu.com</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(2)</strong> Setup a&nbsp;New Virtual machine for Ubuntu Server in the Virtual box (including loading of ISO file)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(3)&nbsp;</strong>Start the Virtual machine and the Installation setup of Ubuntu will be loaded. Select the language and keyboard type. (Screenshot- 487) Use Enter to select.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(4)</strong> The next window will be of Guided Storage Configuration. Select Use the entire disk option by using Tab and Space from the keyboard. (Screenshot- 488). Hit Enter and Confirm the action (Screenshot- 489).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(5)&nbsp;</strong>The next window will be of SSH setup installation. Select the Install OpenSSH server using space and press enter. This will install the OpenSSH server by default. (Screenshot- 490)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(6)&nbsp;</strong>The Installation of the kernel&nbsp;will begin (Screenshot- 491) and <strong>You encounter an Error here&nbsp;</strong>stating &#39;failed unmounting /cdrom&#39;. (Screenshot- 492)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To resolve this error get back to the Virtual Box dashboard and get into the settings of the Ubuntu Server VM being installed and remove the ISO file from Storage &gt; Control: IDE which we loaded previously.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(7) </strong>Open back the VM and press Enter and the Installation process will continue. (Screenshot- 493)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(8)</strong> Enter the Username and Password to Login into the Ubuntu Server (Screenshot- 494, 495)</p>\r\n', '', '', '', '2021-06-16', '2021-06-16', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-06-18 19:12:28', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(258, 227, 42, '<p>In Ubuntu 20.04 LTS server, network configuration is controlled and managed by Netplan utility.<br />\r\nBut during the installation, cloud-init configure a dynamic IP to the interface on the server if the DHCP server is available. so, to configure a static IP, first, we must make sure and confirm that the network interface is not managed by cloud-init.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Open cloud-init file- &quot;<strong>sudo nano /etc/cloud/cloud.cfg.d/subiquity-disable-cloudinit-networking.cfg</strong>&quot; (Screenshot-615)<br />\r\nand make sure entry &ldquo;network: {config: disabled}&rdquo; is there. (Screenshot-616)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Use &ldquo;<strong>ip addr show</strong>&rdquo; command from the console to view IP address<br />\r\nAs we can see (Screenshot-617), a dynamic IP is assigned automatically on interface card &ldquo;enp0s3&rdquo;. So, to make this ip address static, we must edit the netplan configuration file&nbsp; &nbsp;&ldquo;<strong>sudo nano /etc/netplan/00-installer-config.yaml</strong>&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Modify the Netplan configuration file as - (Screenshot-618) and save the file.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Run the following &ldquo;<strong>netplan apply</strong>&rdquo; command to make the above changes into effect. (Screenshot-619)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now run &ldquo;<strong>ip&nbsp;addr show</strong>&rdquo; and &ldquo;<strong>ip route show</strong>&quot; commands to view the IP address and route details. (Screenshot-620)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Output confirms that Static IP has been assigned successfully on interface &lsquo;enp0s3&lsquo;. Even if we reboot the server, this IP address will be consistent.</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Assigning Static IP Address on the Ubuntu Server without using any tool.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-06-28', '2021-06-29', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-06-29 10:10:48', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N');
