(259, 228, 42, '<p>Installed Apache Server on the Ubuntu Server 20.4 LTS</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Start the Ubuntu Server and run the command- &quot;sudo apt install apache2&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This will start the installation process of Apache server</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To check if the installation was&nbsp;done properly, run the command- &quot;apache2 -V&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(Screenshot- 627)</strong></p>\r\n', '<p>While trying to install the Apache on the Ubuntu&nbsp;server I am facing an error as &quot;temporary failure resolving &#39;<a href=\"http://archive.ubuntu.com/\" target=\"_blank\">archive.ubuntu.com</a>&#39; &quot;. On searching&nbsp;for the solutions I tried-&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(1)&nbsp;&nbsp;adding a known DNS server to your system. i.e,&nbsp;echo &quot;nameserver 8.8.8.8&quot; | sudo tee /etc/resolv.conf &gt; /dev/null <strong>(Screenshot-624)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(2)&nbsp; Adding Google DNS Server to the &quot;/etc/resolv.conf&quot; file using command&nbsp;- nano&nbsp; /etc/resolv.conf for opening the file and adding&nbsp;server as nameserver 8.8.8.8 <strong>(Screenshot-626)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>But the error still&nbsp;persists.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I tried pinging 8.8.8.8 and it reverting &quot;Destination host unreachable&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To fix this&nbsp;issue I&#39;ve configured the network adapter of the VM in the Network settings&nbsp;and fixed it to NAT Network. But the issue still persists.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Update</strong>: Downloaded a New ISO file for Ubuntu Server and Re-installed the Ubuntu Server. Only then I was able to install the apache server in the Ubuntu Server</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Installing Apache server on Ubuntu Server</li>\r\n	<li>Troubleshooting methods when Temporary failure errors are generated</li>\r\n	<li>Resolving DNS Service failure issues</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-07-01', '2021-07-03', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-07-02 21:38:44', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(260, 229, 42, '<p>To access the Apache Web Server from the Kali Linux:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(1)&nbsp;</strong>Create a NAT Network and configure Ubuntu Server and Kali Linux on the same NAT Network.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(2)&nbsp;</strong>Try pinging both the machines from each side using their IP addresses respectively.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(3)</strong> Note the IP address of the Ubuntu Server where the Apache Server is Installed.&nbsp; <em>&nbsp;(Screenshot-652)</em>. Here, Our Server&#39;s IP address is 10.0.2.15.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(4)</strong> From Kali Linux, Open any&nbsp;Web Browser and Enter the Server&#39;s IP address and the default Apache Server page will be displayed. <em>(Screenshot-655)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Destination host unreachable</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The error was displayed while trying to access Apache Server from Kali Linux&#39;s browser</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Update: Reconfigured the whole NAT Network and added the required VMs on it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(Screenshot-654)</em></p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Accessing Apache Server from the Kali Linux.</li>\r\n	<li>Resolving &#39;Destination host unreachable&#39; error.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-07-12', '2021-07-13', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-07-13 19:10:18', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(261, 230, 42, '<p><strong>Installing Burpsuite in Kali Linux:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>If there is a previous version of Burpsuite installed on the system, first we need to uninstall it and install the latest version of it.<br />\r\n<strong>Uninstalling Burpsuite:</strong><br />\r\n- Open the Terminal and run the command &#39;<span class=\"marker\">dpkg --list</span>&#39; to get the list of installed applications<br />\r\n- Note the name of the Burpsuite used by the system from the list (Mostly it will be the same as the application name)<br />\r\n- Run the command &#39;<span class=\"marker\">sudo apt-get --purge remove Burpsuite</span>&#39;<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp;This command initiates the uninstallation process of Burpsuite.<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp;Here we use &#39;purge&#39;, which removes all the config files of the application<br />\r\n<em>&nbsp;(Screenshot- 657)</em><br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp;<br />\r\n<strong>&nbsp; Installing Burpsuite:</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp; - At first, we need to download the Burpsuite application file from the Internet using google search &#39;Burpsuite for Linux&#39;.<br />\r\n&nbsp; - After the download is complete, open the Terminal and navigate to the Downloads directory (<span class=\"marker\">cd Downloads/</span>)<br />\r\n&nbsp; - List all the files in the Downloads directory using the &#39;<span class=\"marker\">ls</span>&#39; command to check whether the Burpsuite application file is downloaded properly and copy the name of the application file.<br />\r\n&nbsp; - Run the command &#39;<span class=\"marker\">chmod u+x &lt;Paste the name of app file here&gt;</span>&#39; to initiate the installation of Burpsuite.<br />\r\n&nbsp; - Now finally run the command &#39;<span class=\"marker\">./&lt;Name of the application file&gt;</span>&#39; to start the setup wizard. <em>(Screenshot- 658)</em><br />\r\n&nbsp; - Continue with the setup wizard and Burpsuite will be Installed. <em>(Screenshot- 659,661)</em></p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Installing Burpsuite using Terminal.</li>\r\n	<li>Uninstalling the previous version of application using the terminal.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-07-13', '2021-07-14', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-07-14 11:40:33', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(262, 231, 42, '<p><strong>OWASP ZAP</strong><br />\r\nZAP is an open source tool which is offered by OWASP (Open Web Application Security Project), for penetration testing of your website/web application. It helps you find the security vulnerabilities in your application.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Installing OWASP ZAP:<br />\r\nSteps:</strong><br />\r\n- Download the OWASP ZAP Linux Installer from https://www.zaproxy.org/<br />\r\n- After the file has been downloaded open the terminal and Navigate to the Downloads folder (Command- cd Downloads) and check the OWASP ZAP in the Downloads list (Command- ls)<br />\r\n- Now We&#39;ve to give application the Executive permissions for Installation.<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp;Command- chmod u+x &lt;Name_of_the_App_Frm_Dwnlds_list&gt;<br />\r\n- Now to Install the OWASP ZAP, Execute the command- ./&lt;Name_of_the_App_Frm_Dwnlds_list&gt;<br />\r\n- A New window of Setup wizard will be opened, Follow the setup wizard steps and the Installation is successful.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Please find the attached screenshots of the installation process.</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Overview and Installation of OWASP ZAP in Kali Linux&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-07-23', '2021-07-23', 1, '4', 'Y', 0, '2021-07-23 09:11:18', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(263, 232, 42, '<p><strong>Burp Suite</strong> and <strong>OWASP ZAP</strong> (Zed Attack Proxy) are the most used tools while assessing the security of web applications.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>OWASP ZAP is a free web application security scanner by OWASP while Burp Suite is most used as a proxy tool more than an application security scanner.</li>\r\n	<li>Burp is a commercial closed source tool (which can be extended) developed by a commercial company while ZAP is a free open source tool developed by the community.</li>\r\n	<li>OWASP-ZAP need not be proxy configured to your web browser as it has an inbuilt browser setup that would spider the target server. Also, it mostly has functionalities that directly relate and work based on OWASP concepts.</li>\r\n	<li>Whereas, Burpsuite has to be configured to work as a proxy between your browser and the target server. Also, there is a very limited functionality while using a free version where you cannot even use the scanner option and most other options.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Conclusion</strong>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>BURP ALLOWS YOU TO SCAN AND INSPECT YOUR CUSTOM NEEDS IN EACH AND EVERY SECTION WHICH IS BETTER THAN ZAP</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Differences between Burpsuite and Owasp Zap</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-10-19', '2021-10-20', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-10-20 13:00:57', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(264, 233, 42, '<p><strong>Steps</strong>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(1)</strong> Install the Apache server on the system</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Command: sudo apt-get install apache2 -y</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(2) </strong>Enabling apache server to start:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Command: sudo systemctl enable apache2</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(3)</strong> Check whether the Apache server is running:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Open the web browser and enter the system&#39;s IP Address. You should be getting greetings page from Apache server.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(4) </strong>Now open the terminal and navigate to the file:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>/var/www/html/index.html</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Before that take a backup of the file</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(5)</strong> Backup</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Command: sudo mv&nbsp;/var/www/html/index.html&nbsp;/var/www/html/index.html.bak</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(6)</strong> Now the file is empty and we can enter our website code there.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>command: sudo nano&nbsp;/var/www/html/index.html</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(7)</strong> Define&nbsp;our&nbsp;website code in HTML format. <strong>(Screenshot- 59)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>and save the file</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(8)</strong> Now reload the web page where we have accessed the Apache server, and we can see our code has been executed and defined web page is being displayed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(Screenshot- 58)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '', '2021-11-08', '2021-11-09', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-11-09 07:37:40', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(265, 234, 42, '<p>The Code we&#39;ve defined for the web application is as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;!Doctype html&gt;<br />\r\n&lt;html&gt;<br />\r\n&lt;head&gt;&lt;/head&gt;<br />\r\n&lt;body&gt;<br />\r\n&lt;h1&gt;<br />\r\nGursharan Testing<br />\r\n&lt;/h1&gt;<br />\r\n&lt;h3&gt;<br />\r\nHosting website on Apache server<br />\r\n&lt;/h3&gt;<br />\r\n&lt;/body&gt;<br />\r\n&lt;/html&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now&nbsp;reload the web page where we have accessed the Apache server using the machine&#39;s IP Address, and we can see our code has been executed and defined web page is being displayed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>(Screenshot- 58)</strong></p>\r\n', '', '', '', '2021-11-08', '2021-11-09', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-11-09 08:41:22', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(266, 235, 42, '<p><strong>OWTF </strong>is a short form for&nbsp;<strong>Offensive Web Testing Framework</strong>&nbsp;and it is one of the many OWASP projects to improve security.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>OWTF is commonly used for&nbsp;penetration testing&nbsp;or&nbsp;security assessment. Target users for this tool are pentesters and security professionals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is a framework that tries to unite great tools and make pen testing more efficient.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>OWASP OWTF&nbsp;is a project focused on penetration testing efficiency and alignment of security tests to security standards like the OWASP Testing Guide (v3 and v4), the OWASP Top 10, PTES(Penetration Testing Execution Standards)&nbsp;and NIST(National Institute of Standards and Technology)&nbsp;so that pentesters will have more time to</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>See the big picture and think out of the box</li>\r\n	<li>More efficiently find, verify and combine vulnerabilities</li>\r\n	<li>Have time to investigate complex vulnerabilities like business logic/architectural flaws or virtual hosting sessions</li>\r\n	<li>Perform more tactical/targeted fuzzing on seemingly risky areas</li>\r\n	<li>Demonstrate true impact despite the short timeframes we are typically given to test.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>OWTF is developed on KaliLinux and macOS but it is made for Kali Linux (or other Debian derivatives)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<p>OWASP OWTF Overview</p>\r\n', '', '2021-11-09', '2021-11-10', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-11-10 09:37:56', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(267, 236, 42, '<p>We use a module named&nbsp;<strong>virtualenv</strong>&nbsp;which is a tool to create isolated Python environments. virtualenv creates a folder which contains all the necessary executables to use the packages that a Python project would need. After running this command, a directory named my_name will be created.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Install and use virtulenv with virtualenvwrapper.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Install pip and virtuenv:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>apt installpython3-pip<br />\r\npip installvirtualenv virtualenvwrapper</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Create a backup of your .bashrc file&nbsp;cp ~/.bashrc ~/.bashrc-backup</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Push virtualenvwrapper.sh in to bashrc:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>echo-en &#39;\\n\\n#virtualenvwrapper\\nexport WORKON_HOME=~/virtualenvs\\nsource /usr/local/bin/virtualenvwrapper.sh\\n&#39;&gt;&gt; ~/.bashrc</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Reload settings in bashrc and create virtualenvwrapper home:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>source~/.bashrc<br />\r\nmkdir -p $WORKON_HOME</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Install owtf</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Install dependencies:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>apt installlibcurl4-openssl-dev libssl-dev libpq-dev libxml2-dev libxslt1-dev<br />\r\npip installlxml</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Download the source:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>mkdir bin<br />\r\ncdbin/<br />\r\ngit clonehttps://github.com/owtf/owtf.git</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Install and setup owtf:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>cd owtf<br />\r\npython3 setup.py install</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now start the application with:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>python-m owtf</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '', '2021-12-06', '2021-12-07', 1, '5', 'N', 0, '2021-12-16 06:29:46', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(268, 237, 42, '<p>Open the Owasp Zap in the Kali Linux browser.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As we are going to scan the web application hosted on the Apache server, check if the application is leading correctly by entering the machine&#39;s IP Address in the browser.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Copy the link from the browser where the application is running.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the Owasp Zap enter the copied URL in the Automated Scan section and click on the Attack button.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The scan will take time and the vulnerabilities are listed at the bottom of the application (Screenshot- 87)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For our application, the scan has listed two vulnerabilities (1) X-Frame options header not set (2) X content type options header missing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>which means that this website could be at risk of a clickjacking attack. The X-Frame-Options HTTP header field indicates a policy that specifies whether the browser should render the transmitted resource within a frame or an iframe.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scan report (Screenshot- 88, 89)</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<p>Scanning Web application for vulnerabilities using Owasp Zap</p>\r\n', '', '2021-11-16', '2021-11-18', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-11-18 09:01:43', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(269, 238, 42, '<p>Burp Scan unavailable on Burpsuite Community edition (Screenshot- 104)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Discussed the same with Jeevan in the meeting and we found that Burpsuite has been modified recently and we&nbsp;need a Pro version of Burp to make a successful web application scan.</p>\r\n', '<p>Burp Scan unavailable on Burpsuite Community edition</p>\r\n', '<p>Knowing Process to scan web application with Burpsuite.</p>\r\n', '', '2021-11-18', '2021-11-22', 1, '2', 'Y', 0, '2021-11-22 06:57:17', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(270, 239, 42, '<p>For our application, the Zap scan has listed two vulnerabilities: (<strong>1</strong>) X-Frame options header not set (<strong>2</strong>) X content type options header missing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This means that this website could be at risk of a clickjacking attack. The X-Frame-Options HTTP header field indicates a policy that specifies whether the browser should render the transmitted resource within a frame or an iframe.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scan report (Screenshot- 87, 88, 89)</p>\r\n', '<p>Scanning not available on Burpsuite Community edition.</p>\r\n', '', '', '2021-11-18', '2021-11-22', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-11-22 06:52:58', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(271, 240, 42, '<p><strong>SonarSource COBOL Code Quality and Code Security</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>For Reporting</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>- &nbsp; Bugs<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<br />\r\n- &nbsp; Vulnerabilities<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<br />\r\n- &nbsp; Security Hotspots<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<br />\r\n- &nbsp; Code Smells</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>SonarSource delivers what is probably the best static code analysis you can find on the market for COBOL. Based on our own COBOL parsing technology, it uses the most advanced techniques (pattern matching, dataflow analysis) to analyze code and find Code Smells, Bugs, and Security Vulnerabilities.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Link- </strong>https://www.sonarsource.com/cobol/&nbsp; &nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 595)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>SonarSource has two separate products for analyzing the COBOL Code. One to analyze it on the Cloud(SonarCloud) and another for On-Premise (SonarQube). <em>(Screenshot- 600)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>SonarQube</strong> is an open-source platform developed by SonarSource for continuous inspection of code quality to perform automatic reviews with static analysis of code to detect bugs, code smells, and security vulnerabilities on 20+ programming languages (Including COBOL).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>SonarCloud</strong> is the leading online service to catch Bugs and Security Vulnerabilities in your Pull Requests and throughout your code repositories.</p>\r\n', '', '', '', '2021-06-19', '2021-06-21', 1, '', 'Y', 0, '2021-06-21 10:25:37', '0000-00-00', '', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
