(283, 252, 42, '<p>With a Proxy server, we can capture the browser requests before they reach the Server for which the request was made.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Proxy Tab in the Burpsuite is where we can configure Proxy Server and Turn on/off Intercept which is used to capture the browser requests.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the Proxy section, We can do much more like Configuring Proxy Listeners,&nbsp;specifying which client requests for Intercepting, specifying&nbsp;which Server responses to intercept, etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(Screenshots- 95, 96)</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<p>Proxy Server in Burpsuite</p>\r\n', '', '2021-11-22', '2021-11-22', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-11-22 10:27:14', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(284, 253, 42, '<p>(<strong>1</strong>) Turn the Intercept On in the Burpsuite&#39;s Proxy Section. <em>(Screenshot - 110)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>2</strong>) Now Open the Browser which we have configured with the Proxy using the port number and search for any URL we want to request. (We are searching for youtube.com)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And we can observe that our request for Youtube has not got us results and the browser keeps loading <em>(Screenshot - 107)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>3</strong>) While the browser keeps loading, The Burp&#39;s Intercept window will be popped up showing that our request has not reached the Server but was Captured by the Proxy server.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It shows the complete details of our request being sent to the server <em>(Screenshot - 108)</em></p>\r\n', '<p>CA Certificates issue</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Intercepting the Traffic and Capturing the requests&nbsp; of the browser</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-11-22', '2021-11-23', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-12-30 07:00:55', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(285, 254, 42, '<p>The <strong>Repeater </strong>is designed to take requests that you&rsquo;ve made and to be able to edit and replay them at will.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is a very useful tool for tweaking and refining payloads designed to exploit Cross-Site Scripting or SQL injection vulnerabilities, also known as XSS and SQLI respectively.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Steps: (<strong>1</strong>) Open the tab where the Browser&#39;s Request was captured by our Proxy Server.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>2</strong>) Right-click on the request details and from the options, Click on the &#39;Send to Repeater&#39; button. <em>(Screenshot - 111)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>3</strong>) Now in the menu at the top of the window, Navigate to the Repeater section and we can see the request has been copied with all the details where we can modify the request as required. <em>(Screenshot - 113)</em></p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Overview of Repeater tab and its uses</li>\r\n	<li>Sending Captured requests to the Repeater Tab</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-11-22', '2021-11-23', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-12-30 07:01:21', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(286, 255, 42, '<p>The request captured by the Proxy server is moved to the <strong>Repeater </strong>tab.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And in the repeater tab, we can modify the request and send it to the server using the Se.d button and can observe the server&#39;s response in the right part of the window under the Response section.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We can send any number of requests with different modifications and can get a report on how the server reacts to&nbsp;each request.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Click on the Send button at the top of the window for forwarding the request to the server and to capture the response <em><strong>(Screenshot -112)</strong></em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<p>Concept and use of Repeater and Response tabs in the Burp</p>\r\n', '', '2021-11-23', '2021-11-24', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-12-30 07:04:05', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(287, 256, 42, '<p>In the <strong>proxy </strong>tab, we can see that the intercept is preventing the web browser to load the web page by capturing the browser requests.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As we can view the captured requests, we can forward these requests so that the request reaches the server and gets a response, hence loads the web page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the Proxy tab &gt; Intercept, click on the Forward button to forward the request to the server and for loading the web page.<em> <strong>(Screenshot- 114)</strong></em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>As we have forwarded the request we can observe that some parts of the web page are loaded for now <em><strong>(Screenshot- 115)</strong></em> and the browser is waiting for further requests to reach the server and get a response for the complete loading of the web page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<p>Forwarding the requests and observing the web browser loading into parts.</p>\r\n', '', '2021-11-23', '2021-11-24', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-12-30 07:04:13', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(288, 257, 42, '<p>As we can see once the first request was forwarded, some parts of the browser get loaded and the tab waits for server&#39;s response and keeps on loading <strong><em>(Screenshot- 114,115)</em></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The browser sends requests in a sequence individually and as the requests get a response&nbsp;from the server, the web page loads accordingly.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>When we keep on forwarding the requests, each part of the web page loads accordingly and finally we get the complete page loaded, and at the end there will not be any request left in the Proxy tab. <strong><em>(Screenshot- 116)</em></strong></p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<p>Forwarding requests one by one for complete loading of web page</p>\r\n', '', '2021-11-23', '2021-11-24', 1, '5', 'N', 0, '2021-11-24 08:07:45', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(289, 258, 42, '<p><strong>Burp Intruder</strong> is a tool for automating customized attacks against web applications. It is extremely powerful and configurable, and can be used to perform a huge range of tasks, from simple brute-force guessing of web directories through to active exploitation of complex blind SQL injection vulnerabilities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Working</strong>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Burp intruder is beside the Proxy tab, It works by taking an HTTP request (called the &quot;base request&quot;), modifying the request in various systematic ways, issuing each modified version of the request, and analyzing the application&#39;s responses to identify interesting features.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For each attack, you must specify one or more sets of payloads, and the positions in the base request where the payloads are to be placed.</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Overview of Burp Intruder Tab</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-11-24', '2021-11-24', 1, '5', 'N', 0, '2021-11-24 08:27:54', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(290, 259, 42, '<p>In the Intruder tab of Burpsuite, we can set the attack type we want to perform by selecting from the dropdown present in the &#39;Positions&#39; tab.<em> (Screenshot- 130)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Following are the Attack types we can use only according to the way in which we want to perform the attack.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are four types of attacks:</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>(1) Sniper</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The sniper attack uses only one payload set, and it replaces only one position at a time. It loops through the payload set, first replacing only the first marked position with the payload and leaving all other positions to their original value. After its done with the first position, it continues with the second position.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This attack type is most useful when fuzzing, for example to find XSS or SQL injection. The payload is tried in each position while leaving the other parameters intact, making a successful request more likely.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The sniper attack</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>replaces one position at a time,</li>\r\n	<li>uses one payload set, regardless of the number of positions,</li>\r\n	<li>uses the original values for all positions that have no payload,</li>\r\n	<li>does&nbsp;<em>positions</em>&nbsp;&times;&nbsp;<em>payloads</em>&nbsp;requests.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>For example, consider a URL with two positions. First, the first position is replaced by values from the payload set and the second position is left alone. After all values are exhausted, the second position is used and the first position is left alone.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"Sniper example\" src=\"https://www.sjoerdlangkemper.nl/images/burp-intruder-sniper-table.png\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h2>(2) Battering ram</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The battering ram attack type places the same payload value in all positions. It uses only one payload set. It loops through the payload set and replaces all positions with the payload value.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The battering ram</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>uses one payload set, regardless of the number of positions,</li>\r\n	<li>replaces all positions with the same payload,</li>\r\n	<li>does as many requests as there are payloads in the payload set.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Using the same example URL with the two positions, you can see that the same payload is put in all positions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"Battering ram example\" src=\"https://www.sjoerdlangkemper.nl/images/burp-intruder-battering-ram-table.png\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h2>(3) Pitchfork</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The pitchfork attack type uses one payload set for each position. It places the first payload in the first position, the second payload in the second position, and so on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It then loops through all payload sets at the same time. The first request uses the first payload from each payload set, the second request uses the second payload from each payload set, and so on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This attack type is useful if you have data items that belong together. For example, you have usernames with corresponding passwords and want to know whether they work with this web application. In this case you want to replace both the username and the password in the login request. Load the usernames in the first payload set, and the corresponding passwords in the second payload set. Now only one request for each username/password combination is done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The pitchfork attack</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>uses as many payload sets as there are positions,</li>\r\n	<li>replaces each position with its respective payload,</li>\r\n	<li>does as many requests as the maximum payload set size,</li>\r\n	<li>first payload set goes into first position, etc.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>In this example you can see that it uses the first payload from each set in the first request, and the second payload from each set in the second request.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"Pitchfork example\" src=\"https://www.sjoerdlangkemper.nl/images/burp-intruder-pitchfork-table.png\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h2>(4) Cluster bomb</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The cluster bomb attack tries all different combinations of payloads. It still puts the first payload in the first position, and the second payload in the second position. But when it loops through the payload sets, it tries all combinations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This attack type is useful for a brute-force attack. Load a list of commonly used usernames in the first payload set, and a list of commonly used passwords in the second payload set. The cluster bomb attack will then try all combinations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Note that the number of requests can grow very quickly. If you have 100 usernames and 100 passwords, this attack will perform 10,000 requests. This becomes exponentially worse when using more positions, so this attack is only feasible with a relatively small number of payloads and positions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The cluster bomb attack</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>makes combinations with all payload sets,</li>\r\n	<li>does&nbsp;<em>payloads</em><em>positions</em>&nbsp;requests,</li>\r\n	<li>first payload set goes into first position, etc.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The cluster bomb tries all possible combinations, while still keeping the first payload set in the first position and the second payload set in the second position.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"Cluster bomb example\" src=\"https://www.sjoerdlangkemper.nl/images/burp-intruder-cluster-bomb-table.png\" /></p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Four types of attacks we can set while performing an attack specifically a Dictionary attack in particular positions within a web request.</li>\r\n	<li>What attack to use for different situations.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-12-06', '2021-12-08', 1, '5', 'N', 0, '2021-12-08 07:36:02', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(291, 260, 42, '<p>In the Intruder tab, after setting the Attack type and Positions in the Positions tab, Now for setting up the dictionary attack further, we need to define the Payloads, which can be done in the Payloads tab.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Payloads type consists of four sections, named as (1) Payloads sets</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(2) Payload options</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(3) Payload Processing</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(4) Payload encoding</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>(1) Payloads sets: In this section, we can define the payload type (Eg: Simple list, Numbers, Dates, etc) for different payload sets.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The number of payload sets depends on the Attack type set in the Positions tab.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(Screenshot- 131)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(2) Payload options: Here we need to provide the payload for the set being set in the form defined in the above section (Eg: If the payload type is selected as simple list, we need to upload a list in which words are separated with each line or we can directly upload each record from this section)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(Screenshot- 132)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(3) Payload Processing: Here you can define rules to perform various processing tabson each payload before it is used.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(Screenshot- 133)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(4) Payload encoding: this setting can be used to URL - encode selected characters within the final payload, for safe transmission within HTTP requests.</p>\r\n', '', '', '', '2021-12-06', '2021-12-08', 1, '5', 'N', 0, '2021-12-08 09:20:01', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(292, 261, 42, '<p><strong>Burpsuite Decoder:&nbsp;</strong>can be said as a tool that is used for transforming encoded data into its real form, or for transforming raw data into various encoded and hashed forms. This tool is capable of recognizing several encoding formats using defined techniques.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Burpsuite Decoder <em>(Screenshot- 134) </em>with two sections,&nbsp;which can be interchanged for encoded and decoded text.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are 9 types of decoder format in Burp Suite:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Plain text</li>\r\n	<li>URL</li>\r\n	<li>HTML</li>\r\n	<li>Base64</li>\r\n	<li>ASCII Hex</li>\r\n	<li>Hex</li>\r\n	<li>Octal</li>\r\n	<li>Binary</li>\r\n	<li>Gzip</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Encoding</strong>:<em> (Screenshot- 135)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(1) From the right menu in the Decoder tab, select the input method as Text.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(2) enter the text in the first input section and then click on &#39;Encode as&#39; from the right menu and select your preferred encoding technique (Here we are encoding the text to Base64).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(3) In the second section we can view the encoded text with Base64 encryption for the text we have entered in the upper section. <em>(Screenshot- 135)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Decoding</strong>: <em>(Screenshot- 136)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(1) Get a text encoded with Base64 from anywhere on the Internet or just copy the Base64 text from the previous Encoding process we have performed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(2) Enter the Base64 text in the first input section and from the right menu click on &#39;Decode as&#39; option and select the decoding format as Base64.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(3) In the bottom text box we can see the Base64 text being converted to its real form. <em>(Screenshot- 136)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Using of Decoder tab for encoding and decoding text for different uses.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-12-08', '2021-12-08', 1, '5', 'N', 0, '2021-12-08 18:44:00', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(293, 262, 42, '<p><strong>User options</strong> allow a tester to save or set configurations specific to how they want Burp to be configured upon startup.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are multiple sub-tabs available under the user options tab, which include&nbsp;Connections,&nbsp;SSL,&nbsp;Display, and&nbsp;Misc. <em>(Screenshot- 137)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Connections</strong>:<br />\r\nThe Connections options control how Burp handles platform authentication, upstream proxy servers, SOCKS proxy, timeouts, hostname resolution, and out-of-scope requests.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>TLS</strong>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This tab contains settings for TLS negotiation, Java TLS options, and client and server TLS certificates.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Display</strong>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This tab contains settings for Burp&#39;s user interface, HTTP message display, character set handling, and HTML rendering.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Misc</strong>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This tab contains settings for hotkeys, automatic project backup, Proxy interception, REST API, Proxy history logging, location of temporary files, and performance feedback.</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Overview of user options tab in Burp</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-12-08', '2021-12-09', 1, '5', 'N', 0, '2021-12-09 08:37:09', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(294, 263, 42, '<p><strong>Burp Suite and OWASP ZAP</strong> (Zed Attack Proxy) are the most used tools by security professionals while assessing the security of web applications.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Spider</strong>: Both the tools contain Spider, which is used to crawl the web application in order to&nbsp;map the target web application.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The objective of the mapping is to get a list of endpoints so that their functionality can be observed and potential vulnerabilities can be found. Spidering is done for a simple reason that the more endpoints you gather during your recon process, the more attack surfaces you possess during your actual testing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>OWASP ZAP is a free web application security scanner by OWASP while Burp Suite is most used as a proxy tool more than an application security scanner.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '', '2021-12-13', '2021-12-13', 1, '5', 'N', 0, '2021-12-13 17:34:52', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(295, 264, 42, '<p><strong>ZAP:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zap is an open source tool which is offered by OWASP (Open Web Application Security Project), for penetration testing of your website/web application. It helps you find the security vulnerabilities in your application.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is intended to be used by both those new to application security as well as professional penetration testers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To use ZAP:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Copy the link from the browser where the application is running.</li>\r\n	<li>In the Owasp Zap enter the copied URL in the Automated Scan section and click on the Attack button.</li>\r\n	<li>The scan will take time and the vulnerabilities are listed at the bottom of the application.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><strong>WPScan</strong>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>WPScan is an open source WordPress security scanner. You can use it to scan your WordPress website for known vulnerabilities within the WordPress core, as well as popular WordPress plugins and themes. Since it is a WordPress black box scanner, it mimics a real attacker. This means it does not rely on any sort of access to your WordPress dashboard or source code to conduct the tests. In other words, if WPScan can find a vulnerability in your WordPress website, so can an attacker. WPScan uses the vulnerability database called wpvulndb.com to check the target for known vulnerabilities. The team which develops WPScan maintains this database. It has an ever-growing list of WordPress core, plugins and themes vulnerabilities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To use WP Scan:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Copy the URL of the web application and paste in the wp scan</li>\r\n	<li>In the terminal, type,</li>\r\n	<li>Command: wpscan &ndash;url (URL) -e at -e ap -e u</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><strong>SQL Map:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>sqlmap is an open source penetration testing tool that automates the process of detecting and exploiting SQL injection flaws and taking over of database servers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It comes with a powerful detection engine, many niche features for the ultimate penetration tester and a broad range of switches lasting from database fingerprinting, over data fetching from the database, to accessing the underlying file system and executing commands on the operating system via out-of-band connections.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To use SQLMap:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Open the SQL Map application which is pre installed in the Kali linux. This will open terminal to execute commands.</li>\r\n	<li>Copy the URL of the web application.</li>\r\n	<li>In the terminal, type,</li>\r\n	<li>Command: Sqlmap -u (URL of Victim)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><strong>Skipfish</strong>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Skipfish is a free, open-source Automated Penetration Testing tool available on GitHub made for security researchers. &nbsp;Skipfish is used for&nbsp;information gathering&nbsp;and testing the security of websites and web servers. Skipfish is the easiest and one of the best tools for penetration testing. It provides many integrated tools to perform penetration testing on the target system. This tool is also known as an active&nbsp;web application security reconnaissance&nbsp;tool. This tool functions and makes a map on the console of the targeted site using recursive crawl and dictionary-based probes. This tool gives us all the security checks that are active in the domain. Lastly, this tool generates a report which can be further used for security assessments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To use SkipFish:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Copy the URL of the Web application.</li>\r\n	<li>Open the terminal and by using the keyword &#39;skipfish&#39; we can access the application</li>\r\n	<li>Command: skipfish -o (Output file name to save the results) (URL)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><strong>Commix</strong>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;Commix (short for [comm]and [i]njection e[x]ploiter).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It has a simple environment and it can be used, from web developers, penetration testers or even security researchers to test web applications with the view to find bugs, errors or vulnerabilities related to command injection attacks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By using this tool, it is very easy to find and exploit a command injection vulnerability in a certain vulnerable parameter or string.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To use Commix:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Copy the URL of the Web application.</li>\r\n	<li>Open the terminal and by using the keyword &#39;commix&#39; we can access the application</li>\r\n	<li>Command: commix --url=&quot;(URL)&quot;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Learned about different tools which are available for free and are pre-installed in Kali which can be used for Web applications scanning.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-12-15', '2021-12-15', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-12-25 19:32:06', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
