(303, 271, 42, '<p><strong>Nikto:&nbsp;</strong>is a simple, open-source web server scanner that examines a website and reports back vulnerabilities that it found which could be used to exploit or hack the site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although Nikto is not stealthy. Any site with an intrusion-detection system or other security measures in place will detect that it&#39;s being scanned.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Scanning Web application hosted on Apache Server:&nbsp;</strong>(Screenshot- 164)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Start the Kali Linux and open the Nikto&nbsp;from Vulnerability analysis tools</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Command: nikto -h (URL)&nbsp; &nbsp;<em> (Screenshot- 164)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>here -h is used to define the host.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Scanning by defining the port number and IP Address of the server:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Command: nikto -h (IP Address) -p 80&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em>&nbsp;(Screenshot- 163)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>here -p is used to define the port number on which the scan has to be made.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Scanning and Saving the Scan report in a text file :</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Command: nikto -h http://192.168.0.112/ -o niktoreport1 -F txt&nbsp; &nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 165)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>here -o defines output file name</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-F defines file type in which the report has to be saved.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Nikto scanning tool</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-12-23', '2021-12-27', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-12-27 18:44:39', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(304, 272, 42, '<p><strong>DIRB </strong>is a Web Content Scanner. It looks for existing (and/or hidden) Web Objects. It basically works by launching a dictionary-based attack against a web server and analyzing the responses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Scanning a web application hosted on Apache server:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Web Application for testing:&nbsp; Screenshot- 169</li>\r\n	<li>Scanning using the URL of the hosted web application- Screenshot- 170</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>DIRB comes with a set of preconfigured attack wordlists for easy usage but you can use your custom wordlist.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Default wordlist will be &#39;common.txt&#39;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>We can select another wordlist for directory traversal:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>cd /usr/share/wordlists/dirb&nbsp; &nbsp;</strong><em> (Screenshot- 172)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>ls</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>cd vulns</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>ls</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>DIRB&nbsp;is a content scanner and not a vulnerability scanner.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DIRB&rsquo;s main purpose is to help in professional web application auditing. Specially in security related testing. DIRB looks for specific web objects that other generic CGI scanners can&rsquo;t look for.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Dirb scanner</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-12-27', '2021-12-30', 1, '5', 'N', 0, '2021-12-30 06:54:31', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(305, 273, 42, '<p>Successfully Installed Metasploitable 2 in the Oracle Virtual Box</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Metasploitable </strong>is a purposely vulnerable Linux machine that is used to test security tools and test conventional penetration testing methods on it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Steps executed:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(1) Download Metasploitable 2 disk file from rapid7.com <em>(Screenshot- 803)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(2)&nbsp;Extract the Metasploitable file. and&nbsp;Open the Virtual Box and click the new button on the top right side of your Virtual Box. On the first option, enter the name as Metasploitable and select Type as Linux and Version as Ubuntu 64bit and click Next and go forward.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(3)&nbsp;select the memory size ( RAM),&nbsp;select the type of your Hard disk, and it is VDI(Virtualbox Disk Image),&nbsp;select the Size and location of your Virtual machine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(4) Open the Settings and click on the storage section and for the controller SATA, load the disk file which was extracted previously.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(5) Click on the Start button and let the machine boot up. Once the machine is loaded, log in using the username and password as msfadmin, msfadmin. <em>(Screenshot- 804)</em></p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Downloading and set up Metasploitable 2 in the Oracle Virtual box.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-09-08', '2021-09-09', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-09-09 03:29:28', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(306, 274, 42, '<p>Steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(1) In the Virtual box, click on the Tools &gt; Preferences &gt; Network and click on the create new network icon, and enter a name for the NAT network and save the settings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(2) Open the VM Settings of the Metasploitable2 and Set the Network to the newly created NAT network.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(3) Repeat the 2nd step same as for the Kali Linux.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(4) To check whether both the machines are configured on the same network we will try to ping both the machines from each other side.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>command from Kali Linux: ping 10.0.2.7 <em>(Screenshot- 805)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Command from Metasploitable: ping 10.0.2.4&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 806)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>As the pings were successful we can say that both the machines are on the same network.</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Configuring Metasploitable and Kali on the same NAT Network.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-09-08', '2021-09-09', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-09-09 06:48:51', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(307, 275, 42, '<p><strong>Accessing Damn Vulnerable Web App:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(1) Open&nbsp;the Metasploitable2 VM Settings and from the Network section, configure the machine&#39;s Network to a newly created NAT Network.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(2) Now Configure&nbsp;the Kali Linux on the same NAT network as of the Metasploitable2.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(4) open the Web browser from the Kali Linux and enter the IP Address of the Metasploitable machine followed by a&nbsp;forward slash.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(5) A new&nbsp;Metasploitable page will be displayed with a list of services&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 815)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(6) Click on&nbsp;DVWA from the list and a login page will be displayed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(7) By default the login credentials for the DVWA are Username-&nbsp;admin and password as &#39;password&#39;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(8) Enter the credentials and click login and the DVWA dashboard is opened.&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 810)</em></p>\r\n', '<p>NAT Network getting disconnected and was unable to access the DVWA of Metasploitable2.</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Accessing DVWA from the Kali Linux</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-09-09', '2021-09-09', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-09-13 10:59:26', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(308, 276, 42, '<p><strong>Cracking all the&nbsp;Usernames and Passwords of the DVWA:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>1</strong>) All the Usernames and Passwords are stored in&nbsp;the Database of the Server in hashed formats. So first we need access to the Database.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>2</strong>) From the Kali linux terminal enter the command:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;mysql -u root -h dvwa&#39;&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 817)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>3</strong>) Once the Database is accessible, we need to find the DVWA Database where the credentials are stored. Execute the command: &#39;show databases&#39;&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 817)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>4</strong>) A list of databases will be displayed, from which one of the databases will be dvwa database. to get into the dvwa database run the command- &#39;use dvwa&#39;&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 811)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>5</strong>) Now from the DVWA database,&nbsp;To find the exact table where the Credentials information is stored, search for the tables using the command: &#39;show tables&#39;&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 811)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>6</strong>) A list of tables will be displayed and we need to find the &#39;users&#39; kind of a table from the list which can contain the credentials.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>7</strong>) Execute the SQL command- &#39;select * from users&#39; and we get the table with user names and passwords (BUT HASHED..!!)&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 811)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>8</strong>) To decrypt the hashed passwords we need a tool called John the Ripper. which is specially used in cracking passwords.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>9</strong>) Now create a new text file and enter the user names along with the hashed passwords in the format (username: hashed file)&nbsp;in the text file respectively. <em>(Screenshot- 812)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>10</strong>) Save the file and open a new Terminal and Now we are going to use the John the Ripper tool to crack the hash codes by providing the text file created previously.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(<strong>11</strong>) Heading to the final step,&nbsp;Execute the command of John the Ripper tool in the terminal:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>john --format=raw-MD5&nbsp;loaction/of/the/text/file/with/hashes/ file name.txt</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The passwords are CRACKED..!!&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 813)</em></p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Cracking the username and password of the login page DVWA</li>\r\n	<li>Using John the Ripper</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-09-11', '2021-09-13', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-09-13 13:04:16', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(309, 277, 42, '<p>As the Usernames and Passwords are cracked using the tools NMap, Metasploitable, John the Ripper, and gaining the access to DVWA, Now the security of the DVWA is by default set to High, which we are going to configure to Low.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Open the DVWA home page by logging in with the cracked credentials.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From the left menu click on the &#39;DVWA Security&#39;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And from the security levels dropdown select the level as &#39;low&#39; and click on the &#39;submit&#39; button and the vulnerability levels of DVWA are customized&nbsp;as per the security level.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(SCreenshot- 819)</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up Security levels to customize the Vulnerability levels of the DVWA.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-09-15', '2021-09-15', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-09-15 17:51:55', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(310, 278, 42, '<h2>Please find the attached complete report on all the Vulnerabilities.</h2>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Metasploitable machine got corrupted during the process. re-installed the machine in the Virtual box</li>\r\n	<li>DVWA SQL Injection not working issue. (was resolved by editing the cookies of the web browser and deleting the intercepting cookies)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '<p>Learnt different kinds of attacks for web applications:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Brute forcing</li>\r\n	<li>SQL Injection</li>\r\n	<li>Cross Site Scripting (XSS)</li>\r\n	<li>Malicious File uploading</li>\r\n	<li>File inclusion attack</li>\r\n	<li>CSRF (Cross Site Request Forgery)</li>\r\n	<li>Malicious Command Execution</li>\r\n	<li>XSS Reflected</li>\r\n	<li>XSS Stored&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-09-26', '2021-10-07', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-10-07 07:26:19', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(311, 279, 42, '<p><strong>Please find the attached report defining all the DVWA Vulnerabilities bypassed individually..!!</strong></p>\r\n', '', '', '', '2021-10-08', '2021-10-22', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-10-22 04:30:44', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(312, 280, 42, '<p>Steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1. Start Metasploitable2, the target machine on which phpmyadmin is hosted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2. Also start the host Kali Linux for attacking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3. In the Kali Linux terminal, run Nmap scan for the whole network for knowing IP Address of the target machine (Screenshot- 254)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4. After the target IP address is known, open Burp and in that open burp proxy configured browser.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5. Enter the IP and open the phpmyadmin section from the menu. We can see a login page of phpmyadmin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6. Get back to the Burp and turn on the Intercept and In browser enter any random username and password and try to login. We can see that request is being captured by burp proxy server. (Screenshot- 253)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7. Now send the captured proxy to Intruder tab, where we will perform a dictionary attack.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8. In the intruder tab open&nbsp;the positions&#39; tab, set the attack type to cluster bomb and&nbsp;set username and password as positions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9. Now in the same intruder tab, switch to payloads tab.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9. In the payload tab, Select the payload sets one by one (We have 2, one username and another password)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10. Load the&nbsp;txt files with probable usernames and passwords for dictionary attack respectively. (Screenshot- 255)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11. Now click on start attack button to start the dictionary attack on the phpmyadmin login portal with the given text files containing number of usernames and passwords.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12. In the results, the combination of username and password containing&nbsp;the unique status or length value is the actual username and password to login into the portal.</p>\r\n', '<p>Facing errors while trying to gain the root access</p>\r\n\r\n<p>please find the screenshots below: (193, 194, 195)</p>\r\n', '', '', '2022-01-12', '2022-01-31', 1, '5', 'N', 0, '2022-01-31 07:27:47', '1970-01-01', '54', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(313, 281, 42, '<p>OWASP Mutillidae II is a free, open-source, deliberately vulnerable web application providing a target for web-security training.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mutillidae can be installed on Linux and Windows using LAMP, WAMP, and XAMMP. It is pre-installed on SamuraiWTF and OWASP BWA. The existing version can be updated on these platforms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>from the host kali linux, open the browser and enter the metasploitable2&#39;s IP address since the mutillidae is hosted on it. and navigate to the mutillidae section from the menu</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Screenshot - 196</p>\r\n', '', '', '', '2022-01-10', '2022-01-13', 1, '5', 'N', 0, '2022-01-13 06:52:31', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(314, 282, 42, '<p>OWASP Top 10 2022:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>1. Injection </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Injection occurs when an attacker exploits insecure code to insert (or inject) their own code into a program. Because the program is unable to determine code inserted in this way from its own code, attackers are able to use injection attacks to access secure areas and confidential information as though they are trusted users. Examples of injection include SQL injections, command injections, CRLF injections, and LDAP injections. Application security testing can reveal injection flaws and suggest remediation techniques such as stripping special characters from user input or writing parameterized SQL queries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>2. Broken Authentication</strong> Incorrectly implemented authentication and session management calls can be a huge security risk. If attackers notice these vulnerabilities, they may be able to easily assume legitimate users&#39; identities. Multifactor authentication is one way to mitigate broken authentication. Implement DAST and SCA scans to detect and remove issues with implementation errors before code is deployed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>3. Sensitive Data Exposure</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>APIs, which allow developers to connect their application to third-party services like Google Maps, are great time-savers. However, some APIs rely on insecure data transmission methods, which attackers can exploit to gain access to usernames, passwords, and other sensitive information. Data encryption, tokenization, proper key management, and disabling response caching can all help reduce the risk of sensitive data exposure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>4. XML External Entities</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This risk occurs when attackers are able to upload or include hostile XML content due to insecure code, integrations, or dependencies. An SCA scan can find risks in third-party components with known vulnerabilities and will warn you about them. Disabling XML external entity processing also reduces the likelihood of an XML entity attack.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>5. Broken Access Control</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>If authentication and access restriction are not properly implemented, it&#39;s easy for attackers to take whatever they want. With broken access control flaws, unauthenticated or unauthorized users may have access to sensitive files and systems, or even user privilege settings. Configuration errors and insecure access control practices are hard to detect as automated processes cannot always test for them. Penetration testing can detect missing authentication, but other methods must be used to determine configuration problems. Weak access controls and issues with credentials management are preventable with secure coding practices, as well as preventative measures like locking down administrative accounts and controls and using multi-factor authentication.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>6. Security Misconfiguration</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Just like misconfigured access controls, more general security configuration errors are huge risks that give attackers quick, easy access to sensitive data and site areas. Dynamic testing can help you discover misconfigured security in your application.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>7. Cross-Site Scripting</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>With cross-site scripting, attackers take advantage of APIs and DOM manipulation to retrieve data from or send commands to your application. Cross-site scripting widens the attack surface for threat actors, enabling them to hijack user accounts, access browser histories, spread Trojans and worms, control browsers remotely, and more. Training developers in best practices such as data encoding and input validation reduces the likelihood of this risk. Sanitize your data by validating that it&rsquo;s the content you expect for that particular field, and by encoding it for the &ldquo;endpoint&rdquo; as an extra layer of protection.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>8. Insecure Deserialization</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Deserialization, or retrieving data and objects that have been written to disks or otherwise saved, can be used to remotely execute code in your application or as a door to further attacks. The format that an object is serialized into is either structured or binary text through common serialization systems like JSON and XML. This flaw occurs when an attacker uses untrusted data to manipulate an application, initiate a denial of service (DoS) attack, or execute unpredictable code to change the behavior of the application. Although deserialization is difficult to exploit, penetration testing or the use of application security tools can reduce the risk further. Additionally, do not accept serialized objects from untrusted sources and do not use methods that only allow primitive data types.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>9. Using Components with Known Vulnerabilities</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>No matter how secure your own code is, attackers can exploit APIs, dependencies and other third-party components if they are not themselves secure. A static analysis accompanied by a software composition analysis can locate and help neutralize insecure components in your application. Veracode&rsquo;s static code analysis tools can help developers find such insecure components in their code before they publish an application.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>10. Insufficient Logging and Monitoring</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Failing to log errors or attacks and poor monitoring practices can introduce a human element to security risks. Threat actors count on a lack of monitoring and slower remediation times so that they can carry out their attacks before you have time to notice or react. To prevent issues with insufficient logging and monitoring, make sure that all login failures, access control failures, and server-side input validation failures are logged with context so that you can identify suspicious activity. Penetration testing is a great way to find areas of your application with insufficient logging too. Establishing effective monitoring practices is also essential.</p>\r\n', '', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Owasp Top 10 2022</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2022-05-05', '2022-05-06', 1, '5', 'N', 0, '2022-05-06 11:00:22', '1970-01-01', '54', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
