(390, 356, 57, '<p><strong>License Key: -</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The License Keys section allows you to query for machines with specific License Keys used for installed software. For example, you would use this report</p>\r\n\r\n<p>to find all of the machines with the &quot;KSKQY&quot; License Key used for Adobe Acrobat Reader 9.x installed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Receiving Software follows the same basic flow as outlined above for Hardware. However, you enter License Keys instead of serial numbers for the assets.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For &quot;CAL&quot; License Types the Client Access License Type must be either &ldquo;Server&rdquo; or &ldquo;User&rdquo;. For other License Types, the Client Access License Type must be empty.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>License Key is required for the License Type.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Managing License Key: -</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>IT Asset Management</strong><strong>&nbsp;can record all license keys associated with a license.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Tracking license keys is an administrative convenience that helps you comply with the requirements of your license. However, it does not have any effect on license consumption calculations. If your goal is to bind a particular installation or user to exactly this license, use individual allocations.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Publishers may issue license keys to provide authorization:</strong></li>\r\n	<li>For a single installation</li>\r\n	<li>For a single purchase (covering all the installations authorized by that purchase)</li>\r\n	<li>For a single application (covering multiple installations of that application)</li>\r\n	<li>For a single license (covering all installations authorized under that license).</li>\r\n	<li>You choose the kind of authorization as a License rule on the Identification tab of the same license properties. This choice controls where and how you may record the license key for an individual installation (or user, depending on license type).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Note: -</strong> If you change the license key rule from one active setting (other than No keys) to another, the existing license key values are no longer relevant, and are automatically removed. You can then create the new license keys relevant to your new model, and assign them as required.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>LICENSE KEY RULE: -</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>For a single&nbsp;installation&nbsp;(called&nbsp;<strong>One (single-install) key per installation</strong>)</li>\r\n	<li>For a single&nbsp;purchase&nbsp;(called&nbsp;<strong>One (multi-install) key per installation</strong>)</li>\r\n	<li>For a single&nbsp;application&nbsp;(called&nbsp;<strong>One (multi-install) key per application</strong>)</li>\r\n	<li>For a single&nbsp;license&nbsp;(called&nbsp;<strong>One (multi-install) key per license</strong>).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>For a single&nbsp;installation&nbsp;(called&nbsp;One (single-install) key per installation): -</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>When you assign a license key, you automatically set the Allocation type column to Allocated. This means the installation (or user) has top priority to consume from this license, and may not consume from another, when inventory evidence shows the application is present. This maintains the relationship between the installation/user and this license that is established through the license key.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>For a single&nbsp;purchase&nbsp;(called&nbsp;One (multi-install) key per installation): -</strong></li>\r\n	<li>When you assign a license key, you automatically set the Allocation type column to Allocated. This means the installation (or user) has top priority to consume from this license, and may not consume from another when inventory evidence shows the application is present. This maintains the relationship between the installation/user and this license that is established through the license key.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>For a single&nbsp;application&nbsp;(called&nbsp;One (multi-install) key per application): -</strong></li>\r\n	<li>The&nbsp;One (multi-install) key per application&nbsp;option is restricted to a specific application but allows multiple users to install it by using the same license key. When you choose this licensing rule, multiple users can install one licensed application by using the identical key. If a publisher limits the number of installations on each key, you must manage this limit manually through your assignments</li>\r\n	<li>&nbsp;(IT Asset Management&nbsp;does not track the number of assignments of individual keys).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>For a single&nbsp;license&nbsp;(called&nbsp;One (multi-install) key per license).</strong></li>\r\n	<li>If you choose this licensing rule, you will be able to link a single, shared license key to the license (applicable to all uses of the license). You can then use that license with multiple installations on users&#39; devices.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>License Properties: </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Consumption details</strong></li>\r\n	<li><strong>Entitlements and Consumptions</strong></li>\r\n	<li><strong>Entitlement Limit.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>License Compliance Unknown: </strong>Any License that is missing information required for compliance calculation having compliance status of Unknown (Incomplete License).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The Most important reason for this incomplete software inventory. For Example: Microsoft Server Core and Microsoft Server Processor Licenses require the number of threads, and cores or processor respectively from hardware inventory. Some inventory tools do not include these details, License compliance cannot be accurately calculated without this information, it is given a status of Unknown.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n', '', '<p><strong>In Eracent We have Licence Key Functionality. That allows&nbsp;for generating a report that&nbsp;finds all of the machines with License Key.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Tracking license keys is an administrative convenience that helps you comply with the requirements of your license. However, it does not have any effect on license consumption calculations. If your goal is to bind a particular installation or user to exactly this license, use individual allocations.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>LICENSE KEY RULE: -</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>For a single&nbsp;installation&nbsp;(called&nbsp;<strong>One (single-install) key per installation</strong>)</li>\r\n	<li>For a single&nbsp;purchase&nbsp;(called&nbsp;<strong>One (multi-install) key per installation</strong>)</li>\r\n	<li>For a single&nbsp;application&nbsp;(called&nbsp;<strong>One (multi-install) key per application</strong>)</li>\r\n	<li>For a single&nbsp;license&nbsp;(called&nbsp;<strong>One (multi-install) key per license</strong>).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '2021-08-31', '2021-08-31', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-10-20 09:56:01', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
