(467, 434, 42, '<p>For the above-mentioned requirement, we can use the tool NMap.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Using NMap, we can scan networks in different ways as per our comfort/requirement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I will be demonstrating some scans using NMap in different ways where we get all the open/closed ports:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Prerequisites</strong>: Systems should be connected to the same network. I have a bunch of systems configured&nbsp;on Bridged Network in Virtual Box:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Windows10-192.168.0.101,&nbsp;Ubuntu-192.168.0.105, EVM-192.168.0.137, PFsense-192.168.0.146.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><strong>Nmap scan for a small number of&nbsp; IP Addresses:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Open the terminal and execute the command:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>nmap&nbsp;192.168.0.101&nbsp;192.168.0.146&nbsp;192.168.0.137</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(Screenshot- 69)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The result shows the Ports numbers with their States&nbsp;and specified Service which is running on them.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><strong>Nmap scan for all the systems present on the network:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Command: nmap 192.168.0.0-255 or nmap 192.168.0.0/24</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(Screenshot- 70)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here we have defined the IP Range, which&nbsp;can be altered with any range of IP addresses we want to scan.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><strong>Nmap scan by providing a List of machines:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Steps: (1) Create a text file using the command: nano targets.txt&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 72)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(2) Define&nbsp;the IP Addresses of the machines in separate lines each,&nbsp;for the scan and save the file&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 71)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(3) Now, we will provide the list to the Nmap for scanning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Command: nmap -iL targets.txt</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(Screenshot- 73)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>All the machines defined in the list will be scanned and lists&nbsp;out&nbsp;the Ports numbers with their States&nbsp;and specified Services running on them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><em>Please find the attached report for a clear view.</em></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><strong>If we want to make this whole operation by using the Server names instead of their IP Addresses:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(1) Edit the file /etc/hosts on our host machine using the command:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>sudo nano /etc/hosts&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 75)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(2) Now once the file is opened, map the IP Addresses with their names in the format of IP Addresses followed by the Names(we want to assign&nbsp;to that machine). And IP address and Name separated by a minimum of one space.&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 74)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(3) Save the file and Now we can Ping, Scan that machine with Nmap using its Name.&nbsp;<em>(Screenshot- 74)</em></p>\r\n', '<p>-</p>\r\n', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Nmap scan&nbsp;to scan systems&nbsp;for open ports</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '2021-11-10', '2021-11-11', 1, '5', 'Y', 0, '2021-11-11 09:31:08', '1970-01-01', '28', '', 'N', 'N', 'N', 'N'),
